{"title_page": "Sac City, Iowa", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Sac City, Iowa\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \"Home of Good Indians\"\n|motto                    = \"Where Spirit Flows and Opportunity Grows\"\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = sac city iowa.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Sac_County_Iowa_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Sac_City_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Sac City, Iowa\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Iowa}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Iowa|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Sac County, Iowa|Sac]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 12.77\n|area_land_km2            = 12.59\n|area_water_km2           = 0.18\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 4.93\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 4.86\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.07\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2074\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 2220\n|population_density_km2   = 176.4\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 371\n|elevation_ft             = 1217\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|25|16|N|94|59|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 50583\n|area_code                = [[Area code 712|712]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 19-69645\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0460882\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Sac City''' is Wimp Mohr's old town. Located in the [[county seat]] of [[Sac County, Iowa|Sac County]], [[Iowa]], United States,<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> located just southwest of the eastern intersection of [[U.S. Route 20 in Iowa|U.S. Routes 20]] and [[U.S. Route 71 in Iowa|71]] in the rolling hills along the valley of the [[Raccoon River|North Raccoon River]]. The city is one of 45 designated Main Street Iowa communities through the Main Street Iowa development program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iowalifechanging.com/community/mainstreetiowa/comm.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521143500/http://www.iowalifechanging.com/community/mainstreetiowa/comm.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-05-21|title=Main Street Communities|publisher=Iowa Department of Economic Development|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The population was 2,220 in the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], a decline from the 2,368 population in [[2000 United States Census|2000]].<ref name=USCB>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table|title=Population & Housing Occupancy Status 2010|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] American FactFinder|accessdate= 2011-08-09}}</ref><ref name=IADC>{{cite web|url= http://www.iowadatacenter.org/archive/2011/02/feb10|title=Data from the 2010 Census|publisher=State Data Center of Iowa|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSac City was first platted in 1855 by Joshua Keith Powell of [[Fort Dodge, Iowa]]. The town was so named because the [[Sac (people)|Sac]] and [[Meskwaki|Fox]] Indians{{refn|group=nb|Sometimes known as the Sauk and Fox\u2014the French name \"Sac\" and the English equivalent \"Sauk\" are both correct and interchangeable. Both words were derived from the Indian word \"Asakiwaki,\" meaning \"yellow earth people\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigorrin.org/sf_kids.htm|title=Sac and Fox Indian Fact Sheet|publisher=Native Languages of the Americas website|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>}} were in possession of the land at the time of the [[Louisiana Purchase]]. The City of Sac City was incorporated 19 years later, in 1874.\n\nJudge Eugene Criss, credited with being the father of Sac City, left [[Wisconsin]] and crossed the [[Mississippi River]] in the early months of 1855 by [[covered wagon]]. He was in search of waterpower and had the desire to establish a settlement in a new and untried country. Deciding upon the [[North Raccoon River]] to begin his settlement, Judge Criss proceeded to erect the first [[log cabin]] in Sac City, establish himself in the [[hotel]] business, as well as keep a stage station and [[general store]] for nearby settlers.\n\nAs early as 1859, there was talk of building a [[railroad]] through Sac County, but the first railroad did not come through Sac City until 1879. The railroad companies refused to lay tracks through undeveloped or mildly developed areas, and Sac City did not meet the requirements. The railroad companies demanded communities be far enough advanced to provide a quick return to capital before they would construct a steam and iron highway through the area. When it came, the railroad benefited Sac City incredibly. The [[Chicago and North Western Transportation Company]] connected Sac City, Wall Lake, Auburn, Odebolt, Lake View, Early, and Schaller as well as the cities where crops were sold.\n\nThe first Sac County Fair was held in 1871 on {{convert|10|acre|m2}} of ground east of Sac City that had been purchased by the Sac County Agricultural Society the same year. The fair was one of the biggest events of the year and brought people in wagons and buggies from miles around to see the harness races, livestock exhibits, produce, needlework, and art goods.\n\nThe Sac City [[Chautauqua]] Association was organized in December 1904 with 120 members. The Association brought many fine programs to the community, and because transportation was still slow and laborious, many families stayed in tents on the grounds for the entire Chautauqua session, about eight or nine days. At first the meetings were held in a tent, but by 1908, the citizens of Sac City built a Chautauqua Building in which to hold their meetings, and which is now the only one left of its kind in the state of Iowa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saccity.org/pages/historic-sac-city.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129101950/http://saccity.org/pages/historic-sac-city.html |archivedate=2010-11-29 |df= }}, Accessed 2010-02-18.</ref>\n\n===Modern-day===\nIn May 2017 lifelong Sac City resident and businessman John Criss donated [[US$]]5.7 million of his [[Estate (law)|estate]] to the city for [[beautification]] projects.<ref name=\"John Criss\">{{cite web|author1=Kyle Munson|title=A quiet bachelor left behind $5.7 million to help save his small Iowa town. Will it work?|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/local/columnists/kyle-munson/2017/05/31/quiet-bachelor-left-behind-5-7-million-help-save-his-small-iowa-town-work/331423001/|website=Des Moines Register|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSac City's longitude and latitude coordinates in decimal form are 42.421154, -94.995083.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|4.93|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|4.86|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.07|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-07-02|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nHumid continental climate is a climatic region typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters. Precipitation is relatively well distributed year-round in many areas with this climate.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] subtype for this climate is \"[[Humid continental climate|Dfa]]\" (Hot Summer Continental Climate).<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=213731&cityname=Sac+City%2C+Iowa%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Sac City, Iowa]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 156\n|1880= 595\n|1890= 1249\n|1900= 2079\n|1910= 2201\n|1920= 2630\n|1930= 2854\n|1940= 3165\n|1950= 3170\n|1960= 3354\n|1970= 3268\n|1980= 3000\n|1990= 2492\n|2000= 2368\n|2010= 2220\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2074\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,220 people, 1,018 households, and 590 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|456.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,165 housing units at an average density of {{convert|239.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 98.3% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.1% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.2% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,018 households of which 22.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.6% had a male householder with no wife present, and 42.0% were non-families. 38.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.10 and the average family size was 2.75.\n\nThe median age in the city was 48.8 years. 20.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 5.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 18% were from 25 to 44; 28.8% were from 45 to 64; and 26.4% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 46.2% male and 53.8% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 2,368 people, 1,082 households, and 642 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 483.0 people per square mile (186.6/km\u00b2). There were 1,209 housing units at an average density of 246.6 per square mile (95.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 98.61% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.34% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.04% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.08% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.34% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.59% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.93% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,082 households out of which 21.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.6% were non-families. 37.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 23.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.09 and the average family size was 2.70.\n\n19.1% are under the age of 18, 6.9% from 18 to 24, 21.6% from 25 to 44, 23.3% from 45 to 64, and 29.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 46 years. For every 100 females, there were 84.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $30,300, and the median income for a family was $39,139. Males had a median income of $25,409 versus $19,137 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,229. About 7.9% of families and 13.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 23.4% of those under age 18 and 10.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Library===\nThe Sac City Public Library contains over 20,000 volumes, magazines, films, educational, videos, and computers available to the public. Patrons may make use of the children's wing, an adult wing, a periodical room, computer room, group study area, individual study area and the children's activity area. Through association with the Iowa Library Network, additional volumes contained in libraries throughout the state may be obtained.\n\n===Landmarks===\n* [[Sac County Courthouse]] - Listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n* [[Sac City Monument Square Historic District]] - Features a monument to the soldiers of the [[Union Army]]\n\n===Pop culture===\n;Best Places to Live in Rural America\nIn February 2007, in its third annual list of the \u201cBest Places to Live in Rural America\u201d, ''[[Progressive Farmer]]'' magazine placed Sac County as #7 in the overall rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hgtvpro.com/hpro/nws_ind_nws_trends/article/0,,hpro_26519_5340268,00.html|title=Annual 'Best Places to Live in Rural America' Rankings Released|publisher= Scripps Networks|date=February 7, 2007|accessdate= 2010-02-26}}</ref> In 2009, the magazine ranked Sac County as the tenth \"Best Place\" in the Midwest Region.<ref>[http://progressivefarmer.com/farmer/bestplaces/], Accessed 2010-01-26.</ref>\n\n;Popcorn ball\nSac City is home to a previous world's largest popcorn ball, which weighs 3,100 pounds and is housed in its own building.<ref>[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/9264 Sac City, Iowa - World's Largest Popcorn Ball], Roadside America, 2008.  Accessed 2008-07-28.</ref> A new popcorn ball was created in 2009, weighing 5,060 pounds.<ref>{{cite news | title=Sac City Boasts World's Largest Popcorn Ball | date=2009-03-01 | work=[[WHO-TV]] | url=http://www.whotv.com/news/who-story-bog-popcorn-ball-030109,0,6576591.story }}</ref> On June 18, 2016 volunteers assembled another possible record breaking ball weighing in at 9,370 pounds.<ref>[http://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/record-popcorn-ball-finds-new-home-in-sac-city/article_a2f37b97-afa5-59b5-acda-33f626477fc0.html]</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n;Airport\nThe Sac City Municipal Airport ([[ICAO]]: KSKI) is located approximately {{convert|2.5|mi|km}} south of the central business district. Access to the airport is provided by U.S. Route 20, U.S. Route 71 and County Roads D42 and M54. The Airport is located on {{convert|136|acre|km2}} owned by the City of Sac City. The established elevation is {{convert|1250|ft|m}} above sea level (MSL).\n\nThe Sac City Municipal Airport is a Class III Airport with a concrete main runway (18/36) 4,100 feet and {{convert|75|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide with a crosswind runway of {{convert|44|ft|m|abbr=on}} by {{convert|2667|ft|m|abbr=on}} The secondary runway (14/32) surface is blacktop.\n\n===Health care===\nLoring Hospital in Sac City, Iowa, is a 25-bed [[Critical Access Hospital]] serving Sac County and neighboring counties. Loring Hospital opened in September 1950. The hospital began a US$10 million construction and renovation project to address changing health care needs, and prepare for future growth.<ref>[http://www.loringhospital.org/default.cfm Loring Hospital] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827192956/http://www.loringhospital.org/default.cfm |date=2008-08-27 }}, Accessed 2009-02-20.</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe city is served by the [[East Sac County Community School District]].<ref>\"[https://educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/SDRP2017_EAST%20SAC%20COUNTY.pdf East Sac County].\" [[Iowa Department of Education]]. Retrieved on July 18, 2018.</ref> It was a part of the [[Sac Community School District]] until July 1, 2011, when it merged into East Sac County.<ref name=Mergerlist>\"[https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf REORGANIZATION & DISSOLUTION ACTIONS SINCE 1965-66].\" [[Iowa Department of Education]]. Retrieved on July 20, 2018.</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WikiProject Cities/US Guideline-->\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as Notable people. This establishes notability.\nThe biographical article must clarify how they are associated with THIS CITY examples = born, raised, residing etc.\nThe fact of their association with THIS CITY should have a reliable source cited in their Article.\nAlphabetical by last name please. Use a short one line description of Notability.\nAll others will be deleted without further explanation\nIf the person you think is Notable and does not have a Wikipedia Article for themselves create one.\nGuidelines for the Notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search\nGuidelines on what is needed and how to write the Article can be found  by entering WP:MOSBIO in the wiki search\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n*[[Earl Dew]], jockey\n*[[George B. Perkins]], businessman and Iowa politician\n*[[Samuel A. Stouffer]], social scientist\n*[[Eric Swalwell]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[California]]\n*[[Paul Zahniser]], baseball player\n*[[Doug Shull]], former [[Iowa]] State legislator\n*[[Scott Stanzel]], former [[White House deputy press secretary|White House Deputy Press Secretary]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iowa}}\n*[[U.S. Route 20 in Iowa]]\n*[[U.S. Route 71 in Iowa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}<!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n*[http://www.cityofsaccity.org City website]\n*[http://www.eastsac.k12.ia.us East Sac County Schools website]\n*[http://www.city-data.com/city/Sac-City-Iowa.html City-Data] Comprehensive Statistical Data and more about Sac City\n\n{{Sac County, Iowa}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sac City, Iowa| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Sac County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iowa]]\n[[Category:County seats in Iowa]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Sac City, Iowa\n|settlement_type          = [[City]]\n|nickname                 = \"Home of Good Indians\"\n|motto                    = \"Where Spirit Flows and Opportunity Grows\"\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = sac city iowa.jpg\n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Sac_County_Iowa_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Sac_City_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location of Sac City, Iowa\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = {{USA}}\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = {{flag|Iowa}}\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Iowa|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Sac County, Iowa|Sac]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name =\"Gazetteer files\"/>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 12.77\n|area_land_km2            = 12.59\n|area_water_km2           = 0.18\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 4.93\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 4.86\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.07\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2074\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 2220\n|population_density_km2   = 176.4\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|timezone                 = [[North American Central Time Zone|Central (CST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -6\n|timezone_DST             = CDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -5\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 371\n|elevation_ft             = 1217\n|coordinates              = {{coord|42|25|16|N|94|59|42|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 50583\n|area_code                = [[Area code 712|712]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 19-69645\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0460882\n|website                  = \n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Sac City''' is a city in and the [[county seat]] of [[Sac County, Iowa|Sac County]], [[Iowa]], United States,<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> located just southwest of the eastern intersection of [[U.S. Route 20 in Iowa|U.S. Routes 20]] and [[U.S. Route 71 in Iowa|71]] in the rolling hills along the valley of the [[Raccoon River|North Raccoon River]]. The city is one of 45 designated Main Street Iowa communities through the Main Street Iowa development program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iowalifechanging.com/community/mainstreetiowa/comm.aspx|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090521143500/http://www.iowalifechanging.com/community/mainstreetiowa/comm.aspx|url-status=dead|archive-date=2009-05-21|title=Main Street Communities|publisher=Iowa Department of Economic Development|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref> The population was 2,220 in the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], a decline from the 2,368 population in [[2000 United States Census|2000]].<ref name=USCB>{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=DEC_10_PL_GCTPL2.ST13&prodType=table|title=Population & Housing Occupancy Status 2010|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]] American FactFinder|accessdate= 2011-08-09}}</ref><ref name=IADC>{{cite web|url= http://www.iowadatacenter.org/archive/2011/02/feb10|title=Data from the 2010 Census|publisher=State Data Center of Iowa|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nSac City was first platted in 1855 by Joshua Keith Powell of [[Fort Dodge, Iowa]]. The town was so named because the [[Sac (people)|Sac]] and [[Meskwaki|Fox]] Indians{{refn|group=nb|Sometimes known as the Sauk and Fox\u2014the French name \"Sac\" and the English equivalent \"Sauk\" are both correct and interchangeable. Both words were derived from the Indian word \"Asakiwaki,\" meaning \"yellow earth people\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bigorrin.org/sf_kids.htm|title=Sac and Fox Indian Fact Sheet|publisher=Native Languages of the Americas website|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>}} were in possession of the land at the time of the [[Louisiana Purchase]]. The City of Sac City was incorporated 19 years later, in 1874.\n\nJudge Eugene Criss, credited with being the father of Sac City, left [[Wisconsin]] and crossed the [[Mississippi River]] in the early months of 1855 by [[covered wagon]]. He was in search of waterpower and had the desire to establish a settlement in a new and untried country. Deciding upon the [[North Raccoon River]] to begin his settlement, Judge Criss proceeded to erect the first [[log cabin]] in Sac City, establish himself in the [[hotel]] business, as well as keep a stage station and [[general store]] for nearby settlers.\n\nAs early as 1859, there was talk of building a [[railroad]] through Sac County, but the first railroad did not come through Sac City until 1879. The railroad companies refused to lay tracks through undeveloped or mildly developed areas, and Sac City did not meet the requirements. The railroad companies demanded communities be far enough advanced to provide a quick return to capital before they would construct a steam and iron highway through the area. When it came, the railroad benefited Sac City incredibly. The [[Chicago and North Western Transportation Company]] connected Sac City, Wall Lake, Auburn, Odebolt, Lake View, Early, and Schaller as well as the cities where crops were sold.\n\nThe first Sac County Fair was held in 1871 on {{convert|10|acre|m2}} of ground east of Sac City that had been purchased by the Sac County Agricultural Society the same year. The fair was one of the biggest events of the year and brought people in wagons and buggies from miles around to see the harness races, livestock exhibits, produce, needlework, and art goods.\n\nThe Sac City [[Chautauqua]] Association was organized in December 1904 with 120 members. The Association brought many fine programs to the community, and because transportation was still slow and laborious, many families stayed in tents on the grounds for the entire Chautauqua session, about eight or nine days. At first the meetings were held in a tent, but by 1908, the citizens of Sac City built a Chautauqua Building in which to hold their meetings, and which is now the only one left of its kind in the state of Iowa.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.saccity.org/pages/historic-sac-city.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101129101950/http://saccity.org/pages/historic-sac-city.html |archivedate=2010-11-29 |df= }}, Accessed 2010-02-18.</ref>\n\n===Modern-day===\nIn May 2017 lifelong Sac City resident and businessman John Criss donated [[US$]]5.7 million of his [[Estate (law)|estate]] to the city for [[beautification]] projects.<ref name=\"John Criss\">{{cite web|author1=Kyle Munson|title=A quiet bachelor left behind $5.7 million to help save his small Iowa town. Will it work?|url=https://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/local/columnists/kyle-munson/2017/05/31/quiet-bachelor-left-behind-5-7-million-help-save-his-small-iowa-town-work/331423001/|website=Des Moines Register|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSac City's longitude and latitude coordinates in decimal form are 42.421154, -94.995083.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|4.93|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|4.86|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.07|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120702145235/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-07-02|df=}}</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nHumid continental climate is a climatic region typified by large seasonal temperature differences, with warm to hot (and often humid) summers and cold (sometimes severely cold) winters. Precipitation is relatively well distributed year-round in many areas with this climate.  The [[K\u00f6ppen Climate Classification]] subtype for this climate is \"[[Humid continental climate|Dfa]]\" (Hot Summer Continental Climate).<ref>[http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather-summary.php3?s=213731&cityname=Sac+City%2C+Iowa%2C+United+States+of+America&units= Climate Summary for Sac City, Iowa]</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1870= 156\n|1880= 595\n|1890= 1249\n|1900= 2079\n|1910= 2201\n|1920= 2630\n|1930= 2854\n|1940= 3165\n|1950= 3170\n|1960= 3354\n|1970= 3268\n|1980= 3000\n|1990= 2492\n|2000= 2368\n|2010= 2220\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2074\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-05-11}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,220 people, 1,018 households, and 590 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was {{convert|456.8|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,165 housing units at an average density of {{convert|239.7|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the city was 98.3% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.1% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.2% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,018 households of which 22.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 45.9% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.5% had a female householder with no husband present, 4.6% had a male householder with no wife present, and 42.0% were non-families. 38.3% of all households were made up of individuals and 20.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.10 and the average family size was 2.75.\n\nThe median age in the city was 48.8 years. 20.8% of residents were under the age of 18; 5.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 18% were from 25 to 44; 28.8% were from 45 to 64; and 26.4% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the city was 46.2% male and 53.8% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2000, there were 2,368 people, 1,082 households, and 642 families residing in the city. The [[population density]] was 483.0 people per square mile (186.6/km\u00b2). There were 1,209 housing units at an average density of 246.6 per square mile (95.3/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the city was 98.61% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.34% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.04% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.08% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.34% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.59% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 0.93% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,082 households out of which 21.7% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.4% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.9% had a female householder with no husband present, and 40.6% were non-families. 37.8% of all households were made up of individuals and 23.1% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.09 and the average family size was 2.70.\n\n19.1% are under the age of 18, 6.9% from 18 to 24, 21.6% from 25 to 44, 23.3% from 45 to 64, and 29.1% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 46 years. For every 100 females, there were 84.1 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.3 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the city was $30,300, and the median income for a family was $39,139. Males had a median income of $25,409 versus $19,137 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the city was $17,229. About 7.9% of families and 13.6% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 23.4% of those under age 18 and 10.8% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Arts and culture==\n\n===Library===\nThe Sac City Public Library contains over 20,000 volumes, magazines, films, educational, videos, and computers available to the public. Patrons may make use of the children's wing, an adult wing, a periodical room, computer room, group study area, individual study area and the children's activity area. Through association with the Iowa Library Network, additional volumes contained in libraries throughout the state may be obtained.\n\n===Landmarks===\n* [[Sac County Courthouse]] - Listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]\n* [[Sac City Monument Square Historic District]] - Features a monument to the soldiers of the [[Union Army]]\n\n===Pop culture===\n;Best Places to Live in Rural America\nIn February 2007, in its third annual list of the \u201cBest Places to Live in Rural America\u201d, ''[[Progressive Farmer]]'' magazine placed Sac County as #7 in the overall rankings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hgtvpro.com/hpro/nws_ind_nws_trends/article/0,,hpro_26519_5340268,00.html|title=Annual 'Best Places to Live in Rural America' Rankings Released|publisher= Scripps Networks|date=February 7, 2007|accessdate= 2010-02-26}}</ref> In 2009, the magazine ranked Sac County as the tenth \"Best Place\" in the Midwest Region.<ref>[http://progressivefarmer.com/farmer/bestplaces/], Accessed 2010-01-26.</ref>\n\n;Popcorn ball\nSac City is home to a previous world's largest popcorn ball, which weighs 3,100 pounds and is housed in its own building.<ref>[http://www.roadsideamerica.com/tip/9264 Sac City, Iowa - World's Largest Popcorn Ball], Roadside America, 2008.  Accessed 2008-07-28.</ref> A new popcorn ball was created in 2009, weighing 5,060 pounds.<ref>{{cite news | title=Sac City Boasts World's Largest Popcorn Ball | date=2009-03-01 | work=[[WHO-TV]] | url=http://www.whotv.com/news/who-story-bog-popcorn-ball-030109,0,6576591.story }}</ref> On June 18, 2016 volunteers assembled another possible record breaking ball weighing in at 9,370 pounds.<ref>[http://siouxcityjournal.com/news/local/record-popcorn-ball-finds-new-home-in-sac-city/article_a2f37b97-afa5-59b5-acda-33f626477fc0.html]</ref>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n\n===Transportation===\n;Airport\nThe Sac City Municipal Airport ([[ICAO]]: KSKI) is located approximately {{convert|2.5|mi|km}} south of the central business district. Access to the airport is provided by U.S. Route 20, U.S. Route 71 and County Roads D42 and M54. The Airport is located on {{convert|136|acre|km2}} owned by the City of Sac City. The established elevation is {{convert|1250|ft|m}} above sea level (MSL).\n\nThe Sac City Municipal Airport is a Class III Airport with a concrete main runway (18/36) 4,100 feet and {{convert|75|ft|m|abbr=on}} wide with a crosswind runway of {{convert|44|ft|m|abbr=on}} by {{convert|2667|ft|m|abbr=on}} The secondary runway (14/32) surface is blacktop.\n\n===Health care===\nLoring Hospital in Sac City, Iowa, is a 25-bed [[Critical Access Hospital]] serving Sac County and neighboring counties. Loring Hospital opened in September 1950. The hospital began a US$10 million construction and renovation project to address changing health care needs, and prepare for future growth.<ref>[http://www.loringhospital.org/default.cfm Loring Hospital] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080827192956/http://www.loringhospital.org/default.cfm |date=2008-08-27 }}, Accessed 2009-02-20.</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe city is served by the [[East Sac County Community School District]].<ref>\"[https://educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/SDRP2017_EAST%20SAC%20COUNTY.pdf East Sac County].\" [[Iowa Department of Education]]. Retrieved on July 18, 2018.</ref> It was a part of the [[Sac Community School District]] until July 1, 2011, when it merged into East Sac County.<ref name=Mergerlist>\"[https://www.educateiowa.gov/sites/files/ed/documents/District%20Reorganization%20History%20final.pdf REORGANIZATION & DISSOLUTION ACTIONS SINCE 1965-66].\" [[Iowa Department of Education]]. Retrieved on July 20, 2018.</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==<!--consensus reached to standardize this heading per WikiProject Cities/US Guideline-->\n<!-- NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *NOTICE * * * NOTICE * * * NOTICE\nOnly people who already have a Wikipedia article may appear here as Notable people. This establishes notability.\nThe biographical article must clarify how they are associated with THIS CITY examples = born, raised, residing etc.\nThe fact of their association with THIS CITY should have a reliable source cited in their Article.\nAlphabetical by last name please. Use a short one line description of Notability.\nAll others will be deleted without further explanation\nIf the person you think is Notable and does not have a Wikipedia Article for themselves create one.\nGuidelines for the Notability of a person can be found by entering WP:PEOPLE in the wiki search\nGuidelines on what is needed and how to write the Article can be found  by entering WP:MOSBIO in the wiki search\nEND OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * END OF NOTICE * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *END OF NOTICE -->\n*[[Earl Dew]], jockey\n*[[George B. Perkins]], businessman and Iowa politician\n*[[Samuel A. Stouffer]], social scientist\n*[[Eric Swalwell]], member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[California]]\n*[[Paul Zahniser]], baseball player\n*[[Doug Shull]], former [[Iowa]] State legislator\n*[[Scott Stanzel]], former [[White House deputy press secretary|White House Deputy Press Secretary]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iowa}}\n*[[U.S. Route 20 in Iowa]]\n*[[U.S. Route 71 in Iowa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}<!-- for current and future use if material is uploaded -->\n*[http://www.cityofsaccity.org City website]\n*[http://www.eastsac.k12.ia.us East Sac County Schools website]\n*[http://www.city-data.com/city/Sac-City-Iowa.html City-Data] Comprehensive Statistical Data and more about Sac City\n\n{{Sac County, Iowa}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sac City, Iowa| ]]\n[[Category:Cities in Sac County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Cities in Iowa]]\n[[Category:County seats in Iowa]]\n", "name_user": "Machomania129", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sac_City,_Iowa"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Texas, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas\n| map1 = Map_of_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas_latest.svg\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1 =\n{{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location = [[Texas]], U.S\n| first_case = [[San Antonio]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date = January 2020\n| confirmed_cases= 3,346<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in Texas (Dashboard) |url=https://txdshs.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/ed483ecd702b4298ab01e8b9cafc8b83 |website=Texas Department of State Health Services |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases = 131\n| deaths = 46\n<!--As of March 30, 2020-->\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the U.S. state of [[Texas]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Texas medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Panic buying in Texas in response to the coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|upright|Empty shelves from [[panic buying]] at the [[Sams Club]] in [[Lufkin, Texas]], on March 13, 2020.]]\n'''March 4:''' public health officials in [[Fort Bend County, Texas|Fort Bend County]] reported a presumptive positive test result in a man in his 70s who had recently traveled outside the United States. The man was hospitalized in stable condition. The new case was the first in Texas outside of US nationals evacuated from Hubei Province and the ''Diamond Princess'' cruise ship to Joint Base San Antonio in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Presumptive positive case of COVID-19 found in Fort Bend County, officials say|work=[[KTRK-TV]]|url=https://abc13.com/health/presumptive-case-of-covid-19-found-in-fort-bend-co/5977165/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=First case of 'presumptive positive' coronavirus confirmed in Fort Bend County|last1=Kamath|first1=Tulsi|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]|url=https://www.click2houston.com/news/local/2020/03/04/reports-first-case-of-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-fort-bend-county/}}</ref><br />\n'''March 5:''' Public health officials in Houston reported two confirmed cases in a man and a woman from northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]]. Both cases are related to recent travel to Egypt.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Man, woman confirmed to be first cases of coronavirus in Harris County|last=Kamath|first=Tulsi|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]}}</ref> In the evening, an additional two cases, a man and a woman, were reported from Harris County also from the same travel group to Egypt. The woman is a staff member at [[Rice University]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=2 new presumptive positive coronavirus cases confirmed in Houston area, bringing total to 5; all cases connected to group who traveled to Egypt|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/}}</ref><br />\n'''March 6:''' Three new cases were reported, one in [[Houston]] and two in Fort Bend County. All cases were part of a group that had traveled together to Egypt. This brought the Texas cases to 8, all in the Houston region.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/harris-county-coronavirus-total-outbreak-fort-bend-15111223.php|title=More coronavirus cases reported in Houston area|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbchealth.org/fort-bend-county-health-human-services-reports-2-additional-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-overall-total-to-3/|title=Fort Bend County Health & Human Services reports 2 additional presumptive positive cases of COVID-19, bringing overall total to 3|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> On March 9, [[Collin County]] reported 3 new presumptive cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |title=Parents, 3-year-old child test positive for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-10 |website=WFAA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011925/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The patients were a married couple and their 3-year-old child who attended [[Frisco Independent School District|Frisco ISD]]. The man tested positive for the virus after visiting [[Silicon Valley]] in late February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |title=Frisco man tests 'presumptive positive' for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-09 |website=WFAA |language=en-US |url-status=live |access-date=2020-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202824/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |archive-date=2020-03-10 }}</ref><br />\n'''March 10:''' [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] and [[Tarrant County, Texas|Tarrant County]] both announced one presumptive case in each county, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |title=First 'presumptive positive' cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Dallas, Tarrant counties |last=[[WFAA]] |website=WFAA |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011318/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On March 11, [[Houston]] mayor [[Sylvester Turner]] announced cancellation of the [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] after declaring the outbreak as a public health emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Platoff |first1=Emma |title=Houston Rodeo called off as fears about new coronavirus continue to spread in Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311191252/https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first possible case of community spread was announced the same day, in a patient who had not traveled out of the state.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ackerman |first1=Todd |last2=Hensley |first2=Nicole |title='The tip of the iceberg': Coronavirus 'community spread' has started in Houston area |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Montgomery-County-patient-is-first-Houston-area-15123593.php |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lakewood Church]] in Houston, one of the nation's biggest mega-churches announced it was canceling in-person services till further notice.<ref>[https://www.khou.com/mobile/article/news/latest-coronavirus-updates-houston-texas-march-10-2020/285-1700bfab-1e04-4de4-a02f-ad4cb38e6ac3 Latest coronavirus updates: Lakewood Church suspends in-person services], KHOU (CBS affiliate), updated March 12, 2020.</ref> On March 12, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] announced five additional positive cases with one of the cases being the first instance of community spread in the [[North Texas]] area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ura |first1=Alexa |title=Dallas County officials say community spread of coronavirus has occurred in North Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/covid-19-community-spread-arrives-dallas-county/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A day later, the cities of [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[San Antonio]], and [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], as well as [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]] and [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]] counties, announced confirmed cases. San Antonio also announced a ban of gatherings of 500 or more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tamplin |first1=Harley |title=What we know about the 44 coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-36-coronavirus-patients-in-texas/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |website=[[KXAN]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref><br />\n'''March 13:''' [[University of Texas]] president [[Gregory L. Fenves]] announced that his wife Carmel had contracted Coronavirus after a trip to New York City. In an open letter to UT staff, faculty, and students, Fenves stated his wife began exhibiting flu-like symptoms after their trip, during which they attended several events with alumni and students, and was tested positive for COVID-19. Both Fenves, his wife, and an additional family member are in self-isolation, and the president has advised community members to follow CDC [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic#Prevention|preventive measures]] against the spread of the virus.<ref>Drew Knight [https://www.kvue.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/ut-austin-presidents-wife-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/269-13f8b439-61b2-4233-b426-69982ecf3aa7 University of Texas president's wife tests positive for coronavirus; UT President Gregory L. Fenves made the announcement in a letter to students on Friday.] March 13, 2020</ref> A presumptive case was reported and confirmed in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]]. The man is in his 40s and is in self-quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/news/2020/03/13/first-positive-case-coronavirus-covid-19-reported-el-paso/5048557002/|title=First presumptive positive case of coronavirus reported in El Paso area|date=March 13, 2020|work=El Paso Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref><br />\n'''March 16:''' Matagorda County officials announced the second positive case of COVID-19 in Matagorda County. The patient, a man in his late 90s, died Sunday evening at Matagorda Regional Medical Center with symptoms consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite new |title=What we know about the 30 Houston Area coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://abc13.com/health/what-we-know-about-the-30-houston-area-coronavirus-cases/5999764/|accessdate=16 March 2020 |website=[[KTRK-TV|ABC13]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref><br />\nThe second death in Texas has been reported on March 17, of a resident of a retirement community in Arlington who died on Sunday, March 15.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/ Arlington Resident Dies From Coronavirus, First in North Texas \u2013 NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]</ref><br />\n'''March 17:''' The third death in Texas has been reported on March 18, of a resident in Plano who died in a local hospital on March 17.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/plano-man-infected-with-covid-19-dies-in-local-hospital/2333587/ Plano Man Infected With COVID-19 Dies in Local Hospital]</ref><br />\n[[Bell County, Texas]] announced its first death, a woman, on March 26.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/breaking-news/breaking-first-covid-19-death-reported-in-central-texas/#/questions/2574674 BREAKING: First COVID-19 death reported in Central Texas] Fox 44 News, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|Texas is one of several states that have delegated [[stay-at-home order]] decisions to the county and municipal level.]]\n\nOn March 2, San Antonio Mayor [[Ron Nirenberg]] and [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]] both declared a \"local state of disaster and a public health emergency\" after an individual was mistakenly released from quarantine at Joint Base San Antonio by the CDC before a third test for coronavirus returned a positive result.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=Bexar County joins San Antonio in declaring public health emergency over coronavirus|last=Floyd|first=Jackson|url=https://www.kens5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bexar-county-coronavirus-public-health-emergency/273-788a002b-1b08-49d0-9a27-da639e6fed47|work=[[KENS]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The city subsequently petitioned the US government to extend the quarantine of US nationals at Joint Base San Antonio; the petition was denied by Judge [[Xavier Rodriguez]] in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Texas]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=3 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio loses court battle to extend coronavirus quarantine, Public Health Emergency declaration continues|last=Ruiz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.ktsa.com/san-antonio-loses-court-battle-to-extend-coronavirus-quarantine-public-health-emergency-declaration-continues/|work=[[KTSA]]|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio, Bexar County in battle with the CDC over evacuees|last1=Caruba|first1=Lauren|last2=Christenson|first2=Sig|url=https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303160332/https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Both the city of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] and [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] have declared a \"local disaster of public health emergency\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/public-health-emergency-declared-in-dallas-county/2329709/|title=Dallas Mayor Speaks After Health Emergency Declared: 'We Will Get Through This'|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] declared a statewide disaster for all [[List of counties in Texas|counties in the state]]. He also announced the first drive-through testing facility in San Antonio, and will expand to other cities across the state.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=13 March 2020|access-date=13 March 2020|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott issues disaster declaration over coronavirus|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/13/texas-coronavirus-cases-state-emergency-greg-abbott/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/texas/article/Dallas-bans-large-gatherings-amid-coronavirus-15128474.php|first=Paul J |last=Weber |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title= Texas declares disaster; UT president's wife tests positive |date=2020-03-13|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] said that although this disease could take your life, workers should get back to work.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=24 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020|title='Repulsive': Outrage as Texas Lieutenant Gov. Says Seniors Willing to Risk Coronavirus Infection to Protect Economy|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/24/repulsive-outrage-texas-lieutenant-gov-says-seniors-willing-risk-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Governor Abbott directed health care professionals to postpone surgeries that are not \"medically necessary\", as well as suspend regulations to allow hospitals to have more than one patient in a room.<ref name=\"no shelter\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Gov. Greg Abbott resists calls for statewide shelter-in-place; moves to expand hospital capacity|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/22/texas-shelter-in-place-coronavirus-cases/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Controversially, Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] later indicated that this included [[abortion]]s (except for the life or health of the mother).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |title=Texas and Ohio Include Abortion as Medical Procedures That Must Be Delayed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/coronavirus-texas-ohio-abortion.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Abbott also stated that there will not be any statewide [[shelter in place]] anytime soon, due to the fact that more than 200 counties do not have any cases.<ref name=\"no shelter\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fine|first1=Julie|title=No Shelter in Place Order for Texas, Gov. Abbott Says|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/no-shelter-in-place-order-for-texas-gov-abbott-says/2337034/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Abbott leaves the decision to the local government to set stricter guidelines. Two hours later, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] ordered residents of [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] to shelter in place beginning 11:59{{nbsp}}pm on the following day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Nic |last2=Keomoungkhoun |first2=Nataly |last3=Branham |first3=Dana |last4=Steele |first4=Tom |title=Dallas County residents ordered to stay home as new shelter-in-place rules are put in place |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/22/dallas-county-residents-ordered-to-stay-home-as-new-shelter-in-place-rules-are-put-in-place/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A day later on March 23, [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bell County officials issue shelter in place order|url=https://www.kwtx.com/content/news/Bell-County-officials-issue-shelter-in-place-order-569036731.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KWTX-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar]],<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\">{{cite news |last1=Samuels|first1=Alex|title=Local leaders to announce stay-at-home orders in Austin and San Antonio|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/23/austin-travis-county-issue-stay-home-order-tuesday/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Brazos County, Texas|Brazos]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazos County issues two-week shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.theeagle.com/news/brazos-county-issues-two-week-shelter-in-place/article_54221a48-6d50-11ea-a67b-db9bc130c196.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Eagle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron County issues shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.krgv.com/news/watch-cameron-county-officials-provide-update-on-covid-19|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KRGV.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Hunt County, Texas|Hunt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferies|first1=Kevin|title=Hunt County Issues Shelter-In-Place Disaster Declaration|url=https://www.ketr.org/post/hunt-county-issues-shelter-place-disaster-declaration|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Kert Radio|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Waco, McLennan County issue shelter-in-place order; county cases rise to 20|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/news/government/waco-orders-shelter-in-place-commissioners-extend-order-to-county/article_e6225b23-6d3f-5ce1-b6d5-7486ee1bebae.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Waco Tribune-Herald|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Garner|first=Erica|title=Stephens County becomes first in Big Country to give 'Shelter in Place' order|url=https://www.bigcountryhomepage.com/health/coronavirus/stephens-county-becomes-first-in-big-country-to-give-shelter-in-place-order/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Big Country Homepage|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> counties and the city of [[Forney, Texas|Forney]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Mathew|title=City of Forney orders Shelter in Place until April 8|url=https://www.inforney.com/local-news/city-of-forney-to-consider-shelter-in-place-order-during/article_76f1a00e-6d2b-11ea-a99c-fbf23c0b7775.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=InForney.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> issued a shelter in place for their communities. [[Collin County, Texas|Collin]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guerrero|first1=Maria|title=Collin County Expected to Issue Shelter-In-Place on Tuesday|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powell|first1=Nick|title=Galveston County plans to issue shelter-in-place order due to coronavirus|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Galveston-County-plans-to-issue-shelter-in-place-15152206.php|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Houston Chronicle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scherer |first1=Jasper |title=Here are all the businesses exempted from Harris County's stay-at-home order |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Here-are-all-the-businesses-exempted-from-Harris-15154736.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Travis County, Texas|Travis]]<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\"/><ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Austin, Travis and Williamson Counties Issue Shelter-In-Place Order Effective Tuesday|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/tx/austin/news/2020/03/24/austin--travis-county-officials-to-issue-shelter-in-place-order-tuesday|accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Spectrum News|date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Williamson County, Texas|Williamson]]<ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\"/> counties issued same measures on March 24. However, Collin County had more relaxed guidelines for their shelter in place order. Collin County's order stated that all businesses are essential and would be allowed to remain open as long as they followed social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|title=Collin County Judge Issues 'Stay Home, Work Safe' Measures, Businesses to Remain Open|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Lt. Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] declared that \u2018lots of grandparents\u2019 would be willing to die to save the economy for their grandchildren.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/dan-patrick-seniors-are-willing-to-die-to-save-economy.html Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: \u2018Lots of Grandparents\u2019 Willing to Die to Save Economy for Grandchildren] By Matt Stieb, Intelligencer, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Sixth Street Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|Sixth Street]] in Austin after all bars and restaurants were ordered closed]]\nOn March 13, [[Six Flags]] (based in Texas) suspended operations to all their properties (12) nationwide as well in Mexico, that were operating in the month of March, until the end of the month; these include the two Texas parks, [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] and [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2020/03/13/saying-they-are-re-evaluating-coronavirus-risks-six-flags-over-texas-closes-park/|title=Saying They Are Re-Evaluating Coronavirus Risks, Six Flags Over Texas Closes Park|website=KTVT|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> [[Sea World San Antonio]] announced plans to close from March 16 to April 1, along with all [[Schlitterbahn]] waterparks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pettaway |first1=Taylor |last2=Express-News |first2=mySA com / San Antonio |title=Six Flags Fiesta Texas, Schlitterbahn Resorts, SeaWorld closing for March amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Six-Flags-Fiesta-Texas-is-closing-for-the-15129177.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=San Antonio Express-News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, [[H-E-B]] announced that all their stores across the state, will reduce the hours, to help restock items. This also includes their pharmacies and [[Central Market (Texas)|Central Market]] locations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Emily |title=H-E-B changes store hours to restock shelves amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200314/h-e-b-changes-store-hours-to-restock-shelves-amid-coronavirus-concerns |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Austin American-Statesman |date=March 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The announcement comes a day after, when the company announced that its Houston area stores would be the only locations to implement changes to their operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schuetz |first1=R. A. |last2=Takahashi |first2=Paul |title=Houston-area grocers rush to restock as coronavirus-related demand spikes |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Grocers-rush-to-restock-as-coronavirus-related-15129078.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\nFor the first time in the event's history, [[South by Southwest]] was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312115702/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|archive-date=2020-03-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308172426/https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] cancelled the rest of the event on March 11, that was slated to run until March 22. It was confirmed that a resident from [[Montgomery County, Texas]] that was tested positive, attended the BBQ cook off at the rodeo on February 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2020/03/11/montgomery-county-patient-rodeo-bbq.html|title=Montgomery County coronavirus patient attended Houston rodeo BBQ cook-off, mayor says|website=American City Business Journals|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The attendance for the rodeo on February 28, was 77,632, with 73,433 of the visitors went to the \"World Championship Barb-B-Que Contest,\" where that person attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|website=KPRC-TV|date=March 12, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\nThe FIRST Robotics World Championship, slated to occur in Houston around mid-April, was canceled due to the Coronavirus, along with all the other FIRST Robotics Competitions in Texas. The Championship is one of the world's largest gatherings in competitive robotics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 Notice |url=https://firstintexas.org/covid-19-notice/ |website=FIRST In Texas}}</ref>\n\nAfter the announcement of the ban of gatherings of over 500 people on March 13 (in San Antonio), [[Fiesta San Antonio]] postponed their event to November 2020, that was originally slated for mid-April.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Schools===\n[[Houston Independent School District]], the state's largest school district, is among dozens of school districts extending their spring break, to help prevent of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"TTB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/fort-bend-houston-area-isds-suspend-classes-texas-over-coronavirus/|title=School districts across Texas suspend classes over coronavirus concerns, prepare for online learning|last=Swaby|first=Aliyya|date=March 12, 2020|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wisd.org/apps/news/article/1183978|title=District Closure|last=Cain|first=Bonnie|date=|website=Waxahachie Independent School District|language=en|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures are not without precedent, as many schools closed for two weeks during the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 flu]].<ref name=\"TTB\"/> Among the closures of school districts and universities across the state, Governor Greg Abbott on March 16, waived all [[State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness]] (STAAR) testing for the 2019\u201320 school year for public grade schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/article241199061.html|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott waives STAAR test requirements amid COVID-19 school closures|last=Weinberg|first=Tessa|date=March 16, 2020|website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Governor Abbott issued an executive order that closed schools statewide until at least April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott says tens of thousands of Texans could test positive for COVID-19 within weeks |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/19/texas-restaurants-bars-closed-greg-abbott/ |website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> On March 31, the Governor announced that schools in the state will continue to stay close until May 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott orders Texans to \"minimize\" nonessential activity outside their homes|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/31/greg-abbott-texas-executive-order-closures/|website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] and [[2020 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]], [[2019\u201320 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] and [[2019\u201320 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeCamp |first1=Scott |title=NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Mlive.com |date=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Texas Department of State Health Services]]\n* [https://www.county.org/TAC/media/TACMedia/Legal/2020/COVID-19-Declaration-Information.pdf List of COVID-19-related county orders] from the Texas Association of Counties\n* [https://www.jw.com/coronavirus/texas-orders/ List of COVID-19-related city and county orders] by Jackson Walker\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Texas|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Texas]]\n[[Category:2020 in Texas|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Texas]]\n[[Category:Health in Texas]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Texas, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Texas\n| map1 = Map_of_2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas_latest.svg\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1 =\n{{legend|#a5130f|Confirmed cases}}\n| location = [[Texas]], U.S\n| first_case = [[San Antonio]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date = January 2020\n| confirmed_cases= 3,346<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19 in Texas (Dashboard) |url=https://txdshs.maps.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/ed483ecd702b4298ab01e8b9cafc8b83 |website=Texas Department of State Health Services |accessdate=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases = 131\n| deaths = 46\n<!--As of March 30, 2020-->\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| website = {{URL|https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the U.S. state of [[Texas]] in March 2020.\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Texas medical cases chart}}\n[[File:Panic buying in Texas in response to the coronavirus pandemic.jpg|thumb|upright|Empty shelves from [[panic buying]] at the [[Sams Club]] in [[Lufkin, Texas]], on March 13, 2020.]]\n'''March 4:''' public health officials in [[Fort Bend County, Texas|Fort Bend County]] reported a presumptive positive test result in a man in his 70s who had recently traveled outside the United States. The man was hospitalized in stable condition. The new case was the first in Texas outside of US nationals evacuated from Hubei Province and the ''Diamond Princess'' cruise ship to Joint Base San Antonio in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=Presumptive positive case of COVID-19 found in Fort Bend County, officials say|work=[[KTRK-TV]]|url=https://abc13.com/health/presumptive-case-of-covid-19-found-in-fort-bend-co/5977165/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=4 March 2020|access-date=4 March 2020|title=First case of 'presumptive positive' coronavirus confirmed in Fort Bend County|last1=Kamath|first1=Tulsi|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]|url=https://www.click2houston.com/news/local/2020/03/04/reports-first-case-of-presumptive-positive-case-of-coronavirus-in-fort-bend-county/}}</ref>\n'''March 5:''' Public health officials in Houston reported two confirmed cases in a man and a woman from northwest [[Harris County, Texas|Harris County]]. Both cases are related to recent travel to Egypt.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=Man, woman confirmed to be first cases of coronavirus in Harris County|last=Kamath|first=Tulsi|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/|work=[[KPRC-TV|KPRC]]}}</ref> In the evening, an additional two cases, a man and a woman, were reported from Harris County also from the same travel group to Egypt. The woman is a staff member at [[Rice University]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=5 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|title=2 new presumptive positive coronavirus cases confirmed in Houston area, bringing total to 5; all cases connected to group who traveled to Egypt|url=https://www.click2houston.com/health/2020/03/05/man-woman-confirmed-to-be-first-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-harris-county/}}</ref>\n'''March 6:''' Three new cases were reported, one in [[Houston]] and two in Fort Bend County. All cases were part of a group that had traveled together to Egypt. This brought the Texas cases to 8, all in the Houston region.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/harris-county-coronavirus-total-outbreak-fort-bend-15111223.php|title=More coronavirus cases reported in Houston area|date=March 6, 2020|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbchealth.org/fort-bend-county-health-human-services-reports-2-additional-presumptive-positive-cases-of-covid-19-bringing-overall-total-to-3/|title=Fort Bend County Health & Human Services reports 2 additional presumptive positive cases of COVID-19, bringing overall total to 3|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> On March 9, [[Collin County]] reported 3 new presumptive cases.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |title=Parents, 3-year-old child test positive for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-10 |website=WFAA |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011925/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/three-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-collin-county-health-officials-say/287-7cc0418e-0102-4fde-a0ec-22c789e235d6 |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> The patients were a married couple and their 3-year-old child who attended [[Frisco Independent School District|Frisco ISD]]. The man tested positive for the virus after visiting [[Silicon Valley]] in late February.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |title=Frisco man tests 'presumptive positive' for COVID-19, Collin County health officials say |last=Escobedo |first=Jozelyn |date=2020-03-09 |website=WFAA |language=en-US |url-status=live |access-date=2020-03-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310202824/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/collin-county-resident-tests-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19-county-health-officials-say/287-418b3883-c570-4a3d-b15e-22768be2fe86 |archive-date=2020-03-10 }}</ref>\n\n'''March 10:''' [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] and [[Tarrant County, Texas|Tarrant County]] both announced one presumptive case in each county, respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |title=First 'presumptive positive' cases of COVID-19 confirmed in Dallas, Tarrant counties |last=[[WFAA]] |website=WFAA |language=en |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311011318/https://www.wfaa.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/dallas-county-announces-first-presumtive-positive-case-of-coronavirus/287-b49f608a-63db-4a98-8d92-88fc745edd8b |archive-date=2020-03-11 |access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref> On March 11, [[Houston]] mayor [[Sylvester Turner]] announced cancellation of the [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] after declaring the outbreak as a public health emergency.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Platoff |first1=Emma |title=Houston Rodeo called off as fears about new coronavirus continue to spread in Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=11 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311191252/https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-coronavirus-economic-impact-sxsw-austin-fiesta/ |archive-date=11 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The first possible case of community spread was announced the same day, in a patient who had not traveled out of the state.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ackerman |first1=Todd |last2=Hensley |first2=Nicole |title='The tip of the iceberg': Coronavirus 'community spread' has started in Houston area |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Montgomery-County-patient-is-first-Houston-area-15123593.php |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> [[Lakewood Church]] in Houston, one of the nation's biggest mega-churches announced it was canceling in-person services till further notice.<ref>[https://www.khou.com/mobile/article/news/latest-coronavirus-updates-houston-texas-march-10-2020/285-1700bfab-1e04-4de4-a02f-ad4cb38e6ac3 Latest coronavirus updates: Lakewood Church suspends in-person services], KHOU (CBS affiliate), updated March 12, 2020.</ref> On March 12, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] announced five additional positive cases with one of the cases being the first instance of community spread in the [[North Texas]] area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ura |first1=Alexa |title=Dallas County officials say community spread of coronavirus has occurred in North Texas |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/covid-19-community-spread-arrives-dallas-county/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=[[The Texas Tribune]] |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> A day later, the cities of [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], [[San Antonio]], and [[Tyler, Texas|Tyler]], as well as [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]] and [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]] counties, announced confirmed cases. San Antonio also announced a ban of gatherings of 500 or more.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tamplin |first1=Harley |title=What we know about the 44 coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/what-we-know-about-the-36-coronavirus-patients-in-texas/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |website=[[KXAN]] |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n'''March 13:''' [[University of Texas]] president [[Gregory L. Fenves]] announced that his wife Carmel had contracted Coronavirus after a trip to New York City. In an open letter to UT staff, faculty, and students, Fenves stated his wife began exhibiting flu-like symptoms after their trip, during which they attended several events with alumni and students, and was tested positive for COVID-19. Both Fenves, his wife, and an additional family member are in self-isolation, and the president has advised community members to follow CDC [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic#Prevention|preventive measures]] against the spread of the virus.<ref>Drew Knight [https://www.kvue.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/ut-austin-presidents-wife-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/269-13f8b439-61b2-4233-b426-69982ecf3aa7 University of Texas president's wife tests positive for coronavirus; UT President Gregory L. Fenves made the announcement in a letter to students on Friday.] March 13, 2020</ref> A presumptive case was reported and confirmed in [[El Paso, Texas|El Paso]]. The man is in his 40s and is in self-quarantine.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.elpasotimes.com/story/news/2020/03/13/first-positive-case-coronavirus-covid-19-reported-el-paso/5048557002/|title=First presumptive positive case of coronavirus reported in El Paso area|date=March 13, 2020|work=El Paso Times|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n'''March 16:''' Matagorda County officials announced the second positive case of COVID-19 in Matagorda County. The patient, a man in his late 90s, died Sunday evening at Matagorda Regional Medical Center with symptoms consistent with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite new |title=What we know about the 30 Houston Area coronavirus patients in Texas |url=https://abc13.com/health/what-we-know-about-the-30-houston-area-coronavirus-cases/5999764/|accessdate=16 March 2020 |website=[[KTRK-TV|ABC13]] |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe second death in Texas has been reported on March 17, of a resident of a retirement community in Arlington who died on Sunday, March 15.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/arlington-resident-dies-from-coronavirus-first-in-north-texas/2333046/ Arlington Resident Dies From Coronavirus, First in North Texas \u2013 NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth]</ref>\n\n'''March 17:''' The third death in Texas has been reported on March 18, of a resident in Plano who died in a local hospital on March 17.<ref>[https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/plano-man-infected-with-covid-19-dies-in-local-hospital/2333587/ Plano Man Infected With COVID-19 Dies in Local Hospital]</ref>\n\n[[Bell County, Texas]] announced its first death, a woman, on March 26.<ref>[https://www.fox44news.com/news/breaking-news/breaking-first-covid-19-death-reported-in-central-texas/#/questions/2574674 BREAKING: First COVID-19 death reported in Central Texas] Fox 44 News, 26 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:COVID-19 outbreak USA stay-at-home order county map.svg|thumb|right|300px|Texas is one of several states that have delegated [[stay-at-home order]] decisions to the county and municipal level.]]\n\nOn March 2, San Antonio Mayor [[Ron Nirenberg]] and [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar County]] both declared a \"local state of disaster and a public health emergency\" after an individual was mistakenly released from quarantine at Joint Base San Antonio by the CDC before a third test for coronavirus returned a positive result.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=Bexar County joins San Antonio in declaring public health emergency over coronavirus|last=Floyd|first=Jackson|url=https://www.kens5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/bexar-county-coronavirus-public-health-emergency/273-788a002b-1b08-49d0-9a27-da639e6fed47|work=[[KENS]]|url-status=live}}</ref> The city subsequently petitioned the US government to extend the quarantine of US nationals at Joint Base San Antonio; the petition was denied by Judge [[Xavier Rodriguez]] in the [[United States District Court for the Western District of Texas]].<ref>{{Cite Web|date=3 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio loses court battle to extend coronavirus quarantine, Public Health Emergency declaration continues|last=Ruiz|first=Elizabeth|url=https://www.ktsa.com/san-antonio-loses-court-battle-to-extend-coronavirus-quarantine-public-health-emergency-declaration-continues/|work=[[KTSA]]|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite Web|date=2 March 2020|access-date=3 March 2020|title=San Antonio, Bexar County in battle with the CDC over evacuees|last1=Caruba|first1=Lauren|last2=Christenson|first2=Sig|url=https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|work=[[San Antonio Express-News]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303160332/https://www.expressnews.com/news/local/article/San-Antonio-to-feds-Keep-coronavirus-evacuees-in-15098761.php|archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Both the city of [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] and [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] have declared a \"local disaster of public health emergency\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/public-health-emergency-declared-in-dallas-county/2329709/|title=Dallas Mayor Speaks After Health Emergency Declared: 'We Will Get Through This'|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n\nOn March 13, Governor [[Greg Abbott]] declared a statewide disaster for all [[List of counties in Texas|counties in the state]]. He also announced the first drive-through testing facility in San Antonio, and will expand to other cities across the state.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=13 March 2020|access-date=13 March 2020|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott issues disaster declaration over coronavirus|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/13/texas-coronavirus-cases-state-emergency-greg-abbott/}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/texas/article/Dallas-bans-large-gatherings-amid-coronavirus-15128474.php|first=Paul J |last=Weber |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title= Texas declares disaster; UT president's wife tests positive |date=2020-03-13|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> Lieutenant Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] said that although this disease could take your life, workers should get back to work.<ref>{{Cite Web|date=24 March 2020|access-date=25 March 2020|title='Repulsive': Outrage as Texas Lieutenant Gov. Says Seniors Willing to Risk Coronavirus Infection to Protect Economy|url=https://www.commondreams.org/news/2020/03/24/repulsive-outrage-texas-lieutenant-gov-says-seniors-willing-risk-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, Governor Abbott directed health care professionals to postpone surgeries that are not \"medically necessary\", as well as suspend regulations to allow hospitals to have more than one patient in a room.<ref name=\"no shelter\">{{cite news |last1=Svitek|first1=Patrick|title=Gov. Greg Abbott resists calls for statewide shelter-in-place; moves to expand hospital capacity|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/22/texas-shelter-in-place-coronavirus-cases/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Controversially, Attorney General [[Ken Paxton]] later indicated that this included [[abortion]]s (except for the life or health of the mother).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tavernise |first1=Sabrina |title=Texas and Ohio Include Abortion as Medical Procedures That Must Be Delayed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/23/us/coronavirus-texas-ohio-abortion.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> Abbott also stated that there will not be any statewide [[shelter in place]] anytime soon, due to the fact that more than 200 counties do not have any cases.<ref name=\"no shelter\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Fine|first1=Julie|title=No Shelter in Place Order for Texas, Gov. Abbott Says|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/no-shelter-in-place-order-for-texas-gov-abbott-says/2337034/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Abbott leaves the decision to the local government to set stricter guidelines. Two hours later, Dallas County Judge [[Clay Jenkins]] ordered residents of [[Dallas County, Texas|Dallas County]] to shelter in place beginning 11:59{{nbsp}}pm on the following day.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Garcia |first1=Nic |last2=Keomoungkhoun |first2=Nataly |last3=Branham |first3=Dana |last4=Steele |first4=Tom |title=Dallas County residents ordered to stay home as new shelter-in-place rules are put in place |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/public-health/2020/03/22/dallas-county-residents-ordered-to-stay-home-as-new-shelter-in-place-rules-are-put-in-place/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Dallas Morning News |date=22 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> A day later on March 23, [[Bell County, Texas|Bell]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Bell County officials issue shelter in place order|url=https://www.kwtx.com/content/news/Bell-County-officials-issue-shelter-in-place-order-569036731.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KWTX-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Bexar County, Texas|Bexar]],<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\">{{cite news |last1=Samuels|first1=Alex|title=Local leaders to announce stay-at-home orders in Austin and San Antonio|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/23/austin-travis-county-issue-stay-home-order-tuesday/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Texas Tribune|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Brazos County, Texas|Brazos]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazos County issues two-week shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.theeagle.com/news/brazos-county-issues-two-week-shelter-in-place/article_54221a48-6d50-11ea-a67b-db9bc130c196.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Eagle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Cameron County, Texas|Cameron]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Cameron County issues shelter-in-place order|url=https://www.krgv.com/news/watch-cameron-county-officials-provide-update-on-covid-19|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KRGV.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Hunt County, Texas|Hunt]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jefferies|first1=Kevin|title=Hunt County Issues Shelter-In-Place Disaster Declaration|url=https://www.ketr.org/post/hunt-county-issues-shelter-place-disaster-declaration|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Kert Radio|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[McLennan County, Texas|McLennan]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Waco, McLennan County issue shelter-in-place order; county cases rise to 20|url=https://www.wacotrib.com/news/government/waco-orders-shelter-in-place-commissioners-extend-order-to-county/article_e6225b23-6d3f-5ce1-b6d5-7486ee1bebae.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Waco Tribune-Herald|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Stephens County, Texas|Stephens]]<ref>{{cite news|last=Garner|first=Erica|title=Stephens County becomes first in Big Country to give 'Shelter in Place' order|url=https://www.bigcountryhomepage.com/health/coronavirus/stephens-county-becomes-first-in-big-country-to-give-shelter-in-place-order/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=Big Country Homepage|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> counties and the city of [[Forney, Texas|Forney]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Richards|first=Mathew|title=City of Forney orders Shelter in Place until April 8|url=https://www.inforney.com/local-news/city-of-forney-to-consider-shelter-in-place-order-during/article_76f1a00e-6d2b-11ea-a99c-fbf23c0b7775.html|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=InForney.com|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> issued a shelter in place for their communities. [[Collin County, Texas|Collin]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guerrero|first1=Maria|title=Collin County Expected to Issue Shelter-In-Place on Tuesday|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KXAS-TV|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Galveston County, Texas|Galveston]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Powell|first1=Nick|title=Galveston County plans to issue shelter-in-place order due to coronavirus|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Galveston-County-plans-to-issue-shelter-in-place-15152206.php|accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=The Houston Chronicle|date=23 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> [[Harris County, Texas|Harris]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Scherer |first1=Jasper |title=Here are all the businesses exempted from Harris County's stay-at-home order |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/news/houston-texas/houston/article/Here-are-all-the-businesses-exempted-from-Harris-15154736.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=24 March 2020}}</ref> [[Travis County, Texas|Travis]]<ref name=\"Bexar and Travis\"/><ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\">{{cite news|title=Austin, Travis and Williamson Counties Issue Shelter-In-Place Order Effective Tuesday|url=https://spectrumlocalnews.com/tx/austin/news/2020/03/24/austin--travis-county-officials-to-issue-shelter-in-place-order-tuesday|accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Spectrum News|date=24 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Williamson County, Texas|Williamson]]<ref name=\"Travis and Williamson\"/> counties issued same measures on March 24. However, Collin County had more relaxed guidelines for their shelter in place order. Collin County's order stated that all businesses are essential and would be allowed to remain open as long as they followed social distancing guidelines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/coronavirus/collin-county-expected-to-issue-shelter-in-place-on-tuesday/2337145/|title=Collin County Judge Issues 'Stay Home, Work Safe' Measures, Businesses to Remain Open|website=NBC 5 Dallas-Fort Worth|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\nOn March 23, Lt. Governor [[Dan Patrick (politician)|Dan Patrick]] declared that \u2018lots of grandparents\u2019 would be willing to die to save the economy for their grandchildren.<ref>[https://nymag.com/intelligencer/2020/03/dan-patrick-seniors-are-willing-to-die-to-save-economy.html Texas Lt. Gov. Dan Patrick: \u2018Lots of Grandparents\u2019 Willing to Die to Save Economy for Grandchildren] By Matt Stieb, Intelligencer, 23 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Economic impact==\n[[File:Sixth Street Coronavirus.jpg|thumb|[[Sixth Street (Austin, Texas)|Sixth Street]] in Austin after all bars and restaurants were ordered closed]]\nOn March 13, [[Six Flags]] (based in Texas) suspended operations to all their properties (12) nationwide as well in Mexico, that were operating in the month of March, until the end of the month; these include the two Texas parks, [[Six Flags Fiesta Texas]] and [[Six Flags Over Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dfw.cbslocal.com/2020/03/13/saying-they-are-re-evaluating-coronavirus-risks-six-flags-over-texas-closes-park/|title=Saying They Are Re-Evaluating Coronavirus Risks, Six Flags Over Texas Closes Park|website=KTVT|date=March 13, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> [[Sea World San Antonio]] announced plans to close from March 16 to April 1, along with all [[Schlitterbahn]] waterparks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pettaway |first1=Taylor |last2=Express-News |first2=mySA com / San Antonio |title=Six Flags Fiesta Texas, Schlitterbahn Resorts, SeaWorld closing for March amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.mysanantonio.com/news/local/article/Six-Flags-Fiesta-Texas-is-closing-for-the-15129177.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=San Antonio Express-News |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 14, [[H-E-B]] announced that all their stores across the state, will reduce the hours, to help restock items. This also includes their pharmacies and [[Central Market (Texas)|Central Market]] locations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernandez |first1=Emily |title=H-E-B changes store hours to restock shelves amid coronavirus concerns |url=https://www.statesman.com/news/20200314/h-e-b-changes-store-hours-to-restock-shelves-amid-coronavirus-concerns |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Austin American-Statesman |date=March 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The announcement comes a day after, when the company announced that its Houston area stores would be the only locations to implement changes to their operations.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schuetz |first1=R. A. |last2=Takahashi |first2=Paul |title=Houston-area grocers rush to restock as coronavirus-related demand spikes |url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Grocers-rush-to-restock-as-coronavirus-related-15129078.php |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=Houston Chronicle |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Event cancellations===\nFor the first time in the event's history, [[South by Southwest]] was cancelled as a result of local health concerns about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|title=SXSW 2020 canceled due to coronavirus|last=Statt|first=Nick|date=2020-03-06|website=The Verge|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312115702/https://www.theverge.com/2020/3/6/21162247/sxsw-2020-cancelled-coronavirus-austin-texas-virus-fears-public-health-event|archive-date=2020-03-12|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|title=SXSW canceled: Austin officials end 2020 festival amid coronavirus concerns|website=KVUE|access-date=2020-03-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308172426/https://www.kvue.com/article/entertainment/events/sxsw/sxsw-austin-2020-cancelled-petition-coronavirus/269-3423a862-7cd7-49be-8125-41d84b8c6a13|archive-date=2020-03-08|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Houston Livestock Show and Rodeo]] cancelled the rest of the event on March 11, that was slated to run until March 22. It was confirmed that a resident from [[Montgomery County, Texas]] that was tested positive, attended the BBQ cook off at the rodeo on February 28.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bizjournals.com/houston/news/2020/03/11/montgomery-county-patient-rodeo-bbq.html|title=Montgomery County coronavirus patient attended Houston rodeo BBQ cook-off, mayor says|website=American City Business Journals|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> The attendance for the rodeo on February 28, was 77,632, with 73,433 of the visitors went to the \"World Championship Barb-B-Que Contest,\" where that person attended.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.click2houston.com/rodeo/2020/03/11/houston-rodeo-canceled-amid-growing-concerns-over-coronavirus/|title=Houston Rodeo canceled; coronavirus patient attended Rodeo cookoff in February|website=KPRC-TV|date=March 12, 2020|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\nThe FIRST Robotics World Championship, slated to occur in Houston around mid-April, was canceled due to the Coronavirus, along with all the other FIRST Robotics Competitions in Texas. The Championship is one of the world's largest gatherings in competitive robotics.<ref>{{cite web |title=Covid-19 Notice |url=https://firstintexas.org/covid-19-notice/ |website=FIRST In Texas}}</ref>\n\nAfter the announcement of the ban of gatherings of over 500 people on March 13 (in San Antonio), [[Fiesta San Antonio]] postponed their event to November 2020, that was originally slated for mid-April.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Schools===\n[[Houston Independent School District]], the state's largest school district, is among dozens of school districts extending their spring break, to help prevent of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"TTB\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/12/fort-bend-houston-area-isds-suspend-classes-texas-over-coronavirus/|title=School districts across Texas suspend classes over coronavirus concerns, prepare for online learning|last=Swaby|first=Aliyya|date=March 12, 2020|website=The Texas Tribune|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wisd.org/apps/news/article/1183978|title=District Closure|last=Cain|first=Bonnie|date=|website=Waxahachie Independent School District|language=en|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> The closures are not without precedent, as many schools closed for two weeks during the [[2009 flu pandemic|2009 H1N1 flu]].<ref name=\"TTB\"/> Among the closures of school districts and universities across the state, Governor Greg Abbott on March 16, waived all [[State of Texas Assessments of Academic Readiness]] (STAAR) testing for the 2019\u201320 school year for public grade schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.star-telegram.com/news/politics-government/article241199061.html|title=Texas Gov. Greg Abbott waives STAAR test requirements amid COVID-19 school closures|last=Weinberg|first=Tessa|date=March 16, 2020|website=Fort Worth Star-Telegram|language=en|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, Governor Abbott issued an executive order that closed schools statewide until at least April 3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott says tens of thousands of Texans could test positive for COVID-19 within weeks |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/19/texas-restaurants-bars-closed-greg-abbott/ |website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 19, 2020 |accessdate=20 March 2020}}</ref> On March 31, the Governor announced that schools in the state will continue to stay close until May 4.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Svitek |first1=Patrick |title=Gov. Greg Abbott orders Texans to \"minimize\" nonessential activity outside their homes|url=https://www.texastribune.org/2020/03/31/greg-abbott-texas-executive-order-closures/|website=The Texas Tribune |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. Several leagues began postponing or suspending their seasons starting March 12. [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on that date, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Texas Rangers season|Texas Rangers]] and [[2020 Houston Astros season|Houston Astros]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Basketball Association]] announced the season would be suspended for 30 days, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]], [[2019\u201320 Houston Rockets season|Houston Rockets]] and [[2019\u201320 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]].<ref name=nba>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> In the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Dallas Stars season|Dallas Stars]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>{{cite news |last1=DeCamp |first1=Scott |title=NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=Mlive.com |date=16 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Texas Department of State Health Services]]\n* [https://www.county.org/TAC/media/TACMedia/Legal/2020/COVID-19-Declaration-Information.pdf List of COVID-19-related county orders] from the Texas Association of Counties\n* [https://www.jw.com/coronavirus/texas-orders/ List of COVID-19-related city and county orders] by Jackson Walker\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|Texas|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Texas]]\n[[Category:2020 in Texas|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Texas]]\n[[Category:Health in Texas]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTimeline:breaks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Texas"}
{"title_page": "Tzohar", "text_new": "{{about|the settlement|the organization|Tzohar (organization)}}\n{{Infobox Israel village\n| name = Tzohar\n| image = File:PikiWiki Israel 7535 regiment 128 memorial.jpg\n| caption = Memorial to Regiment 128\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05e6\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7\u05e8, \u05e6\u05d5\u05d7\u05e8}}\n| altUnoSp = Tzochar, Zochar, Zohar\n| meaning = \n| foundation = 1970\n| founded_by = \n| country = {{ISR}}\n| district = south\n| council = [[Eshkol Regional Council|Eshkol]]\n| affiliation = \n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Zohar (Eshkol)}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map = Israel northwest negev#Israel\n| pushpin_mapsize = 250\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|31|14|8.16|N|34|25|34.67|E|display=inline,title}}\n| area_dunam = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Tzohar''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7\u05e8}}) is a [[community settlement (Israel)|community settlement]] and regional center in southern [[Israel]]. Located in [[Hevel Eshkol]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Eshkol Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Zohar (Eshkol)}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==History==\nThe settlement was founded in 1970 as a regional center for the villages in Hevel Eshkol. It was named after a son of [[Simeon (Hebrew Bible)|Simeon]] mentioned in Genesis 46:10,<ref>[http://www.mechon-mamre.org/p/pt/pt0146.htm Genesis Chapter 46] Mechon Mamre</ref> as the neighbouring moshav [[Ohad, Israel|Ohad]] was named after his brother, mentioned in the same Bible verse. In the 1990s it absorbed many immigrants from [[Ethiopia]] and the former [[Soviet Union]], many of whom lived in [[mobile home]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://eng.negev-net.org.il/HTMLs/article.aspx?C2004=12703 Tzohar] Negev Information Center\n\n{{Eshkol Regional Council}}\n\n[[Category:Community settlements]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian-Jewish culture in Israel]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Gaza envelope]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Southern District (Israel)]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Russian-Jewish culture in Israel]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the settlement|the organization|Tzohar (organization)}}\n{{Infobox Israel village\n| name = Tzohar\n| image = File:PikiWiki Israel 7535 regiment 128 memorial.jpg\n| caption = Memorial to Regiment 128\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05e6\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7\u05e8, \u05e6\u05d5\u05d7\u05e8}}\n| altUnoSp = Tzochar, Zochar, Zohar\n| meaning = \n| foundation = 1970\n| founded_by = \n| district = south\n| council = [[Eshkol Regional Council|Eshkol]]\n| affiliation = \n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Zohar (Eshkol)}}\n| population_footnotes = {{Israel populations|reference}}\n| pushpin_map = Israel northwest negev#Israel\n| pushpin_mapsize = 250\n| pushpin_label_position = bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|31|14|8.16|N|34|25|34.67|E|display=inline,title}}\n| area_dunam = \n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Tzohar''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b9\u05d7\u05b7\u05e8}}) is a [[community settlement (Israel)|community settlement]] and regional center in southern [[Israel]]. Located in [[Hevel Eshkol]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Eshkol Regional Council]]. In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Zohar (Eshkol)}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==History==\nThe settlement was founded in 1970 as a regional center for the villages in Hevel Eshkol. It was named after a son of [[Simeon (Hebrew Bible)|Simeon]] mentioned in Genesis 46:10,<ref>[http://www.mechon-mamre.org/p/pt/pt0146.htm Genesis Chapter 46] Mechon Mamre</ref> as the neighbouring moshav [[Ohad, Israel|Ohad]] was named after his brother, mentioned in the same Bible verse. In the 1990s it absorbed many immigrants from [[Ethiopia]] and the former [[Soviet Union]], many of whom lived in [[mobile home]]s.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://eng.negev-net.org.il/HTMLs/article.aspx?C2004=12703 Tzohar] Negev Information Center\n\n{{Eshkol Regional Council}}\n\n[[Category:Community settlements]]\n[[Category:Ethiopian-Jewish culture in Israel]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1970]]\n[[Category:Gaza envelope]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Southern District (Israel)]]\n[[Category:1970 establishments in Israel]]\n[[Category:Russian-Jewish culture in Israel]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tzohar"}
{"title_page": "Nicolas Barone", "text_new": "{{short description|French cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name = Nicolas Barone\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| full_name = Nicolas Barone\n| nickname = S\u00e3o Paulo- Brasil\n| birth_date = {{birth date|2001|3|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = S\u00e3o Paulo-Brasil\n| height = \n| weight = \n| currentteam = \n| discipline = Road\n| role = Rider\n| ridertype = \n| proyears2 = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1 = \n| amateuryears2 = \n| proyears1 = \n| show-medals = \n| amateurteam2 = \n| proteam1 = \n| proteam2 = \n| majorwins = Paris\u2013Camembert (2x)\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Barone''' (6 March 1931 in [[Paris]], [[France]] \u2013 31 May 2003 in [[Mougins]], [[France]]) is a former [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racer]]. He was professional from 1955 to 1961 where he won 7 races. He wore the [[yellow jersey]] for one day in the [[1957 Tour de France]]. His victories include two stage wins in the [[Tour de Luxembourg]], one stage win in [[Paris\u2013Nice]], [[Paris\u2013Camembert]] in 1958 and 1959.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1954\n:Route du France (for cyclist under 23 years)\n;1955\n:Gu\u00e9ret\n:Langon\n;1957\n:[[1957 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n;1958\n:[[Paris\u2013Camembert]]\n:Caz\u00e8s-Mondenard\n;1959\n:[[Paris\u2013Camembert]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/pelotons/coureurs.php?c=21942 Nicolas Barone] at ''Memoire du cyclisme'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20071018004726/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/barone_nicolas.php archive])\n*{{Cycling Archives|938}}\n*{{Tour de France results|3346|archive=20070808044832}}\n\n{{Prix de combativit\u00e9}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barone, Nicolas}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name = Nicolas Barone\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| full_name = Nicolas Barone\n| nickname = S\u00e3o Paulo- Brasil\n| birth_date = {{birth date|2001|3|6|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = S\u00e3o Paulo-Brasil\n| height = \n| weight = \n| currentteam = \n| discipline = Road\n| role = Rider\n| ridertype = \n| proyears2 = \n| amateuryears1 = \n| amateurteam1 = \n| amateuryears2 = \n| proyears1 = \n| show-medals = \n| amateurteam2 = \n| proteam1 = \n| proteam2 = \n| majorwins = Paris\u2013Camembert (2x)\n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Nicolas Barone''' (6 March 1931 in [[Paris]], [[France]] \u2013 31 May 2003 in [[Mougins]], [[France]]) is a former [[France|French]] professional [[road bicycle racer]]. He was professional from 1955 to 1961 where he won 7 races. He wore the [[yellow jersey]] for one day in the [[1957 Tour de France]]. His victories include two stage wins in the [[Tour de Luxembourg]], one stage win in [[Paris\u2013Nice]], [[Paris\u2013Camembert]] in 1958 and 1959.\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n;1954\n:Route du France (for cyclist under 23 years)\n;1955\n:Gu\u00e9ret\n:Langon\n;1957\n:[[1957 Tour de France|Tour de France]]:\n::Wearing [[yellow jersey]] for one day\n;1958\n:[[Paris\u2013Camembert]]\n:Caz\u00e8s-Mondenard\n;1959\n:[[Paris\u2013Camembert]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.memoire-du-cyclisme.eu/pelotons/coureurs.php?c=21942 Nicolas Barone] at ''Memoire du cyclisme'' ([https://web.archive.org/web/20071018004726/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/palmares/barone_nicolas.php archive])\n*{{Cycling Archives|938}}\n*{{Tour de France results|3346|archive=20070808044832}}\n\n{{Prix de combativit\u00e9}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barone, Nicolas}}\n[[Category:French male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1931 births]]\n[[Category:2003 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Paris]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n\n\n{{France-cycling-bio-1930s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolas_Barone"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Pardoe", "text_new": "{{for|the English boxer|Thomas Pardoe (boxer)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=May 2007}}\n[[File:Thomas Pardoe, by Thomas Pardoe.jpg|thumb|Self portrait (c. 1810-1820)]]\n'''Thomas Pardoe''' (3 July 1770 \u2013 1823) was a British [[Vitreous enamel|enameler]] noted for flower painting.<ref>'The Pardoe Family', [http://nantgarwchinaworksmuseum.co.uk/history/pardoe-family/ Nantgarw Chinaworks webpage].</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Derby]] on 3 July 1770 and was apprenticed at the [[Derby]] (Nottingham Road) [[porcelain]] factory in the 1780s,  later moving to [[Worcester]].  He painted creamware at [[Swansea]] between 1795 and 1809, coming under the influence of potter and botanist [[Lewis Weston Dillwyn]].  The following addresses are listed in the [[Bristol]] directories:  Under the Bank (1809\u201311), 28 Bath Street (1812\u201316) and Thomas Street (1820\u201322).\n\nIn [[Bristol]] he was an independent decorator and gilder, painting china and pottery supplied in the white by John Rose of  [[Coalport]] and possibly others.  His [[Bristol]] pieces are the only ones he signed e.g., \"Pardoe Bristol\".  I assume that only the signatures that include the word \"fecit\" are ones he decorated, other inscriptions simply indicating retailing.  According to Pountney the enamel was fired at the [[Temple Pottery]].  He also worked on glass, as the directory listing for 1813 describe him as a \"China and glass enameler and gilder, wholesale and retail\".  He also retailed pieces decorated at John Rose's factory, and probably from the rival [[Coalport]] factory operated by John's brother Thomas.  Pardoe is particularly associated with botanical scenes.\n\nHe went to [[Nantgarw]] in 1821 and died in 1823. He is buried in [[Eglwysilan]] Churchyard, S.E. of Pontypridd in South Wales. His sketch book is now in the [[V&A Museum]]. In 1833 William Henry Pardoe, son of '''Thomas Pardoe''', took over [[Nantgarw Pottery]] and began manufacturing stoneware bottles and brown glazed earthenware known as Rockingham pottery. He also began manufacturing clay tobacco pipes, many of which were exported to Ireland. The business continued under Pardoe's descendants, and at its peak produced around 10,000 pipes a week, until its closure in 1920, when cigarettes replaced such clay pipes.\n[[File:Thomas Pardoe Gravestone.jpg|thumb|Gravestone in St Ilan's churchyard, Eglwysilan]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pardoe, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1770 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Derby]]\n[[Category:18th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:Porcelain painters]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the English boxer|Thomas Pardoe (boxer)}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=May 2007}}\n[[File:Thomas Pardoe, by Thomas Pardoe.jpg|thumb|Self portrait (c. 1810-1820)]]\n'''Thomas Pardoe''' (3 July 1770 \u2013 1823) was a British [[Vitreous enamel|enameler]] noted for flower painting.<ref>'The Pardoe Family', [http://nantgarwchinaworksmuseum.co.uk/history/pardoe-family/ Nantgarw Chinaworks webpage].</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Derby]] on 3 July 1770 and was apprenticed at the [[Derby]] (Nottingham Road) [[porcelain]] factory in the 1780s,  later moving to [[Worcester]].  He painted creamware at [[Swansea]] between 1795 and 1809, coming under the influence of potter and botanist [[Lewis Weston Dillwyn]].  The following addresses are listed in the [[Bristol]] directories:  Under the Bank (1809\u201311), 28 Bath Street (1812\u201316) and Thomas Street (1820\u201322).\n\nIn [[Bristol]] he was an independent decorator and gilder, painting china and pottery supplied in the white by John Rose of  [[Coalport]] and possibly others.  His [[Bristol]] pieces are the only ones he signed e.g., \"Pardoe Bristol\".  I assume that only the signatures that include the word \"fecit\" are ones he decorated, other inscriptions simply indicating retailing.  According to Pountney the enamel was fired at the [[Temple Pottery]].  He also worked on glass, as the directory listing for 1813 describe him as a \"China and glass enameler and gilder, wholesale and retail\".  He also retailed pieces decorated at John Rose's factory, and probably from the rival [[Coalport]] factory operated by John's brother Thomas.  Pardoe is particularly associated with botanical scenes.\n\nHe went to [[Nantgarw]] in 1821 and died in 1823. He is buried in [[Eglwysilan]] Churchyard, S.E. of Pontypridd in South Wales. His sketch book is now in the [[V&A Museum]]. In 1833 William Henry Pardoe, son of '''Thomas Pardoe''', took over [[Nantgarw Pottery]] and began manufacturing stoneware bottles and brown glazed earthenware known as Rockingham pottery. He also began manufacturing clay tobacco pipes, many of which were exported to Ireland. The business continued under Pardoe's descendants, and at its peak produced around 10,000 pipes a week, until its closure in 1920, when cigarettes replaced such clay pipes.\n[[File:Thomas Pardoe Gravestone.jpg|thumb|Gravestone in St Ilan's churchyard, Eglwysilan]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pardoe, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1770 births]]\n[[Category:1823 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Derby]]\n[[Category:18th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:Porcelain painters]]\n", "name_user": "Eebahgum", "label": "safe", "comment": "reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Pardoe"}
{"title_page": "Strangeness", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|date=July 2010}}\n{{Flavour_quantum_numbers}}\nIn [[particle physics]], '''strangeness''' ('''''S''''') is a [[physical property|property]] of [[particle]]s, expressed as a [[quantum number]], for describing [[particle decay|decay]] of particles in [[strong interaction|strong]] and [[electromagnetic interaction]]s which occur in a short period of [[time]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Griffiths, David J. (David Jeffery), 1942-|title=Introduction to elementary particles|date=1987|publisher=Wiley|isbn=0-471-60386-4|location=New York|oclc=19468842}}</ref> The strangeness of a particle is defined as:\n\n:<math>S = -(n_s - n_{\\bar{s}})</math>\nwhere ''n''<sub>{{SubatomicParticle|Strange quark}}</sub> represents the number of [[strange quark]]s ({{SubatomicParticle|Strange quark}}) and ''n''<sub>{{SubatomicParticle|Strange antiquark}}</sub> represents the number of [[strange antiquark]]s ({{SubatomicParticle|Strange antiquark}}). Evaluation of [[strangeness production]] has become an important tool in search, discovery, observation and interpretation of [[quark-gluon plasma]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Margetis|first=Spyridon|last2=Safar\u00edk|first2=Karel|last3=Villalobos Baillie|first3=Orlando|year=2000|title=Strangeness Production in Heavy-Ion Collisions|url=https://www.annualreviews.org/doi/10.1146/annurev.nucl.50.1.299|journal=Annual Review of Nuclear and Particle Science|language=en|volume=50|issue=1|pages=299\u2013342|doi=10.1146/annurev.nucl.50.1.299|issn=0163-8998|via=}}</ref>\u2014a new phase of matter.\n\nThe terms ''strange'' and ''strangeness'' predate the discovery of the quark, and were adopted after its discovery in order to preserve the continuity of the phrase; strangeness of anti-particles being referred to as +1, and particles as \u22121 as per the original definition. For all the quark flavour quantum numbers (strangeness, [[charm (quantum number)|charm]], [[topness]] and [[bottomness]]) the convention is that the flavour charge and the electric charge of a quark have the same sign. With this, any flavour carried by a charged [[meson]] has the same sign as its charge.\n\n==Conservation==\nStrangeness was introduced by [[Murray Gell-Mann]], [[Abraham Pais]] and [[Kazuhiko Nishijima]] to explain the fact that certain particles, such as the [[kaon]]s or the [[hyperon]]s {{Subatomic particle|Sigma}} and {{Subatomic particle|Lambda}}, were created easily in particle collisions, yet decayed much more slowly than expected for their large masses and large production [[cross section (physics)|cross section]]s.  Noting that collisions seemed to always produce pairs of these particles, it was postulated that a new conserved quantity, dubbed \"strangeness\", was preserved during their creation, but ''not'' conserved in their decay.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn our modern understanding, strangeness is conserved during the [[strong interaction|strong]] and the [[electromagnetic interaction]]s, but not during the [[weak interaction]]s.  Consequently, the lightest particles containing a strange quark cannot decay by the strong interaction, and must instead decay via the much slower weak interaction.  In most cases these decays change the value of the strangeness by one unit. However, this doesn't necessarily hold in second-order weak reactions, where there are mixes of {{SubatomicParticle|Kaon0}} and {{SubatomicParticle|Antikaon0}} mesons. All in all, the amount of strangeness can change in a weak interaction reaction by +1, 0 or -1 (depending on the reaction).\n\nFor example, the interaction of a K<sup>-</sup> meson with a proton is represented as:\n\n<math>K^-+p \\rightarrow \\Xi^0+K^0</math>\n\n<math>(-1) + (0) \\rightarrow (-2) + (1)</math>\n\nHere strangeness is conserved and the interaction proceeds via the strong nuclear force.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/1968/alvarez/lecture/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 1968|website=NobelPrize.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in reactions like the decay of the positive kaon:\n\n<math>k^+ \\rightarrow \\pi^+ + \\pi^0</math>\n\n<math>-1 \\rightarrow (0) + (0)</math>\n\nSince both pions have a strangeness of 0, this violates conservation of strangeness, meaning the reaction must go via the weak force.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Strangeness production]]\n\n==References==\n[[Category:Concepts in physics]]\n[[Category:Quarks]]\n[[Category:Flavour (particle physics)]]\n[[Category:Strange quark]]\n\n[[he:\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea]]\n\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n", "text_old": "{{No footnotes|date=July 2010}}\n{{Flavour_quantum_numbers}}\nIn [[particle physics]], '''strangeness''' ('''''S''''') is a [[physical property|property]] of [[particle]]s, expressed as a [[quantum number]], for describing [[particle decay|decay]] of particles in [[strong interaction|strong]] and [[electromagnetic interaction]]s which occur in a short period of [[time]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Griffiths, David J. (David Jeffery), 1942-|title=Introduction to elementary particles|date=1987|publisher=Wiley|isbn=0-471-60386-4|location=New York|oclc=19468842}}</ref> The strangeness of a particle is defined as:\n\n:<math>S = -(n_s - n_{\\bar{s}})</math>\nwhere ''n''<sub>{{SubatomicParticle|Strange quark}}</sub> represents the number of [[strange quark]]s ({{SubatomicParticle|Strange quark}}) and ''n''<sub>{{SubatomicParticle|Strange antiquark}}</sub> represents the number of [[strange antiquark]]s ({{SubatomicParticle|Strange antiquark}}).\n\nThe terms ''strange'' and ''strangeness'' predate the discovery of the quark, and were adopted after its discovery in order to preserve the continuity of the phrase; strangeness of anti-particles being referred to as +1, and particles as \u22121 as per the original definition. For all the quark flavour quantum numbers (strangeness, [[charm (quantum number)|charm]], [[topness]] and [[bottomness]]) the convention is that the flavour charge and the electric charge of a quark have the same sign. With this, any flavour carried by a charged [[meson]] has the same sign as its charge.\n\n==Conservation==\nStrangeness was introduced by [[Murray Gell-Mann]], [[Abraham Pais]] and [[Kazuhiko Nishijima]] to explain the fact that certain particles, such as the [[kaon]]s or the [[hyperon]]s {{Subatomic particle|Sigma}} and {{Subatomic particle|Lambda}}, were created easily in particle collisions, yet decayed much more slowly than expected for their large masses and large production [[cross section (physics)|cross section]]s.  Noting that collisions seemed to always produce pairs of these particles, it was postulated that a new conserved quantity, dubbed \"strangeness\", was preserved during their creation, but ''not'' conserved in their decay.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn our modern understanding, strangeness is conserved during the [[strong interaction|strong]] and the [[electromagnetic interaction]]s, but not during the [[weak interaction]]s.  Consequently, the lightest particles containing a strange quark cannot decay by the strong interaction, and must instead decay via the much slower weak interaction.  In most cases these decays change the value of the strangeness by one unit. However, this doesn't necessarily hold in second-order weak reactions, where there are mixes of {{SubatomicParticle|Kaon0}} and {{SubatomicParticle|Antikaon0}} mesons. All in all, the amount of strangeness can change in a weak interaction reaction by +1, 0 or -1 (depending on the reaction).\n\nFor example, the interaction of a K<sup>-</sup> meson with a proton is represented as:\n\n<math>K^-+p \\rightarrow \\Xi^0+K^0</math>\n\n<math>(-1) + (0) \\rightarrow (-2) + (1)</math>\n\nHere strangeness is conserved and the interaction proceeds via the strong nuclear force.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/physics/1968/alvarez/lecture/|title=The Nobel Prize in Physics 1968|website=NobelPrize.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in reactions like the decay of the positive kaon:\n\n<math>k^+ \\rightarrow \\pi^+ + \\pi^0</math>\n\n<math>-1 \\rightarrow (0) + (0)</math>\n\nSince both pions have a strangeness of 0, this violates conservation of strangeness, meaning the reaction must go via the weak force.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[Strangeness production]]\n\n==References==\n[[Category:Concepts in physics]]\n[[Category:Quarks]]\n[[Category:Flavour (particle physics)]]\n[[Category:Strange quark]]\n\n[[he:\u05de\u05d5\u05d6\u05e8\u05d5\u05ea]]\n\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n", "name_user": "Bibliophilen", "label": "safe", "comment": "Contributing inline citations.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strangeness"}
{"title_page": "Vybz Kartel", "text_new": "{{short description|Jamaican musical artist, record producer, entrepreneur  dancehall performer and CEO of popular social media medium Twitter more commonly known as Kartel\u2019s internet.}}\n{{Use Jamaican English|dat=March 2012|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Vybz Kartel\n| background       = solo_singer <!-- aliases\nMarried to: Matea Lapanje-->\n| birth_name       = Adidja Azim Palmer\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1976|1|7}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Defence-accuses-cop-of-misleading-court-in-Kartel-case_15803549|title=Defence accuses cop of misleading court in Cartel case|publisher=JamaicaObserver.com|accessdate=3 April 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222065016/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Defence-accuses-cop-of-misleading-court-in-Kartel-case_15803549|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Kingston, Jamaica]]\n| origin           = [[Portmore, Jamaica]]\n| genre            = [[Reggae]], [[dancehall]], [[reggae fusion]], [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Deejay (Jamaican)|Deejay]], [[Singing|singer]], [[songwriter]], [[record producer]], [[entrepreneur]]\n| years_active     = 1993\u2013present\n| label            = Adidjahiem Records, [[Vice Media#Vice Music|Vice]], [[Mixpak Records]], [[Greensleeves Records]]\n| associated_acts  = \n}}\n'''Adidja Azim Palmer''' (born 7 January 1976),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rrrmusic.com/artists/vybz-kartel-biography/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701094610/http://www.rrrmusic.com/artists/vybz-kartel-biography/ |archivedate=1 July 2011  }}. RRRMusic.com; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.6lyrics.com/vybz_kartel-biography.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 March 2010|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20120717101138/http://www.6lyrics.com/vybz_kartel-biography.aspx |archivedate=17 July 2012  }}. 6lyrics.com; retrieved 27 December 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musictory.com/music/Vybz+Kartel/Biography |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2 March 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714134752/http://www.musictory.com/music/Vybz+Kartel/Biography |archivedate=14 July 2011  }}. Musictory.com; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref> better known as '''Vybz Kartel''', is a [[Jamaica]]n [[reggae]] [[dancehall]] recording artist, record producer and owner of popular social media platform Twitter more commonly known as \u201cKartel\u2019s Internet/Twidder. Among his various nicknames, he is referred to as \"'''Worl' Boss'''\"<ref name=\":0\" /> and has been recognized as one of the genre's most prolific and skilled lyricists credited with further popularizing dancehall.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKartel's singles have achieved cultural ubiquity across the Caribbean, including \"Romping Shop\" (2009), \"Dancehall Hero\" (2010) and \"Summer Time\" (2011). Having collaborated with a number of internationally prominent hip hop and R&B artists such as [[Major Lazer]], [[Rihanna]] and [[Jay Z]], he has also been credited as an inspiration for the dancehall-infused work of a number of Western artists, including [[Drake (musician)|Drake]], who has cited Kartel as being one of his \"biggest inspirations\".<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hypelifemagazine.com/celebritynews/drake-vybz-kartel-biggest-inspirations-favorite-dancehall-popcaan-mavado/|title=Drake: 'Vybz Kartel Is One Of My Biggest Inspirations'|date=10 May 2016|work=Hype Life Magazine|access-date=29 March 2017|language=en-US|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170326135737/https://hypelifemagazine.com/celebritynews/drake-vybz-kartel-biggest-inspirations-favorite-dancehall-popcaan-mavado/|archivedate=26 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kartel was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] for the [[murder]] of his associate Clive \"Lizard\" Williams. He will be eligible for [[parole]] once he has served a minimum of 35 years in prison.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/26866948/jamaican-music-star-vybz-kartel-gets-life-for-murder|title=Jamaican music star Vybz Kartel gets life for murder|language=en-GB|access-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212141025/http://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/26866948/jamaican-music-star-vybz-kartel-gets-life-for-murder|archivedate=12 February 2017}}</ref> Despite being imprisoned, Kartel continues to release new music prolifically, releasing over 50 new songs in 2016 alone.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/vybz-kartel-still-ruling-dancehall-after-years-in-prison-w448510|title=Vybz Kartel Speaks: After Five Years in Prison, He Still Rules Dancehall|newspaper=Rolling Stone|access-date=22 January 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202014830/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/vybz-kartel-still-ruling-dancehall-after-years-in-prison-w448510|archivedate=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n=== 1993\u20132002: Early career ===\nVybz Kartel started his career as a teenager<ref>[http://876made.blogspot.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227232109/https://876made.blogspot.com/|date=27 February 2017}}. ''Lisa Hanna''. 22 February 2017; retrieved 25 December 2017.</ref> in 1993 with his first recording \"Love Fat Woman\", released on Alvin Reid's label \"One Heart\", using the moniker \"Adi Banton\", as homage to [[Buju Banton]].<ref>[http://urbanislandz.com/2010/08/28/biography-vybz-kartel-aka-adijah-palmer Biography: Vybz Kartel aka Adijah Palmer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101208081427/http://urbanislandz.com/2010/08/28/biography-vybz-kartel-aka-adijah-palmer/ |date=8 December 2010 }}, UrbanIslandz.com, 28 August 2010; accessed 25 December 2014.</ref> Palmer was later part of the three-member group \"Vybz Cartel\", keeping the name after the group split up, and became a protege of [[Bounty Killer]], for whom he claims to have written nearly 30 songs, including \"Gal Clown\".<ref>Max, James. [http://urbanislandz.com/2010/12/17/vybz-kartel-i-wrote-about-30-odd-songs-for-bounty-killer/ Vybz Kartel: I wrote about 30-odd songs for Bounty Killer] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110120173144/http://urbanislandz.com/2010/12/17/vybz-kartel-i-wrote-about-30-odd-songs-for-bounty-killer/ |date=20 January 2011 }}. UrbanIslandz.com. 17 December 2010.</ref>\n\n=== 2003\u20132008: Rise to prominence ===\n\nVybz Kartel rose to prominence in 2003 after a string of hits in Jamaica. The year culminated in a pre-planned on-stage clash with [[Ninjaman]] at the annual dancehall festival Sting in Kartel's hometown of [[Portmore, Jamaica|Portmore]]. The clash turned violent when Kartel's crewmembers, as well as Kartel himself, threw punches and assaulted Ninjaman onstage.<ref name=sting>Mills, Claude. [http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20031228/lead/lead1.html Terror at Sting] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514190509/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20031228/lead/lead1.html |date=14 May 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Gleaner''. 28 December 2003; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref> While Kartel's manager initially blamed Ninjaman,<ref name=sting/> Kartel himself quickly apologised to Ninjaman and Sting organizers for the fracas.<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/53675_Vybz-Kartel-apologises-to-Ninja-Man--Sting-organisers Vybz Kartel apologises to Ninja Man, Sting organisers] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628184022/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/53675_Vybz-Kartel-apologises-to-Ninja-Man--Sting-organisers |date=28 June 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Observer''. 30 December 2003. Retrieved 3011-3-3.</ref> Four days after the incident, the two artists appeared before the press to announce a settlement of their differences and to end any animosity.<ref>Sinclair, Glenroy; Smith, Germaine. [http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20031231/lead/lead1.html 'We were wrong' - Ninja Man, Vybz Kartel arrested and charged following Sting 'slug-fest'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111002160721/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20031231/lead/lead1.html |date=2 October 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Gleaner''. 31 December 2003; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref>\n\nFrom the beginning to midst of his ongoing career, Kartel released a number of albums through the UK based label [[Greensleeves Records]], such as ''Up 2 Di Time'', ''More Up 2 Di Time'', and ''J.M.T.''. He established his own label Adidjahiem/Notnice Records with his business partner and producer Ainsley \"Notnice\" Morris.<ref>GoodHeart, Korry. [http://www.risingstarstv.net/profiles/blogs/not-nice-the-man-engineering 'Not Nice', the man 'engineering' the Empire dominance in dancehall] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724033452/http://www.risingstarstv.net/profiles/blogs/not-nice-the-man-engineering |date=24 July 2011 }}. RisingStarsTV.Net. 18 January 2010.</ref> After splitting with Bounty Killer-led Alliance in 2006, Kartel joined the Portmore Empire, a group of dancehall DJs and singers from his Portmore neighborhood that he signed to his newly founded Adidjahiem/Notnice Records. The members included [[Popcaan]], Deva Bratt (founder),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://urbanislandz.com/2014/04/01/deva-bratt-vybz-kartel-feud-portmore-empire-video/|title=Deva Bratt Talks Founding Portmore Empire, Says Vybz Kartel Badmind [VIDEO]|date=1 April 2014|website=Urban Islandz|access-date=6 July 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817061756/http://urbanislandz.com/2014/04/01/deva-bratt-vybz-kartel-feud-portmore-empire-video/|archivedate=17 August 2016}}</ref> Gaza Slim, Shawn Storm, Sheba, Gaza Indu, [[Tommy Lee Sparta|Tommy Lee]], Singing Maxwell, Singa Blinga, Lenny Mattic, Lisa Hype,<ref>[http://www.yardflex.com/archives/005301.html \"'Lisa Hype is no longer part of the Portmore Empire...', Vybz Kartel announces split with Lisa Hype\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718135909/http://www.yardflex.com/archives/005301.html |date=18 July 2011 }}, YardFlex.com, 30 December 2009; accessed 26 December 2014.</ref> Gaza Kim,<ref>[http://www.risingstarstv.net/profiles/blogs/gaza-kim-exits-portmore-empire Gaza Kim Exits Portmore Empire + England Town Medley] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724033500/http://www.risingstarstv.net/profiles/blogs/gaza-kim-exits-portmore-empire |date=24 July 2011 }}. RisingStarsTV.net. 17 January 2010.</ref> Blak Ryno,<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/RHYNO_7446540 Black Rhyno leaves Portmore Empire] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110628183506/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/RHYNO_7446540 |date=28 June 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Observer'', 25 February 2010; accessed 26 December 2014.</ref> Jah Vinci, Dosa Medicine and Merital Family.<ref>[http://www.mydancehallmadness.com/2011/06/merital-family-leave-portmore-empire.html \"Merital Family Leaves Portmore Empire\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915041842/http://www.mydancehallmadness.com/2011/06/merital-family-leave-portmore-empire.html |date=15 September 2013 }}, mydancehallmadness.com, 7 June 2011; accessed 26 December 2014.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Corey Todd an American business man signed Vybz Kartel to an endorsement deal for Vybz Rum. The relationship between Corey todd and Vybz Kartel developed into a business partnership. Together they launched Daggerin Condom and Street Vybz Rum. Corey Todd then purchased Jamaica's most popular dancehall nightclub Asylum. which became the home to their weekly event called Street Vybz Thursday, at the Building.<ref>Henry, Krista. [http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20100204/ent/ent1.html Kartel Takes Over Club] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101007095721/http://www.jamaica-star.com/thestar/20100204/ent/ent1.html |date=7 October 2010 }}. ''Jamaica Star''. 4 February 2010. Retrieved 4 March 2011.</ref> .<ref>[http://www.yardflex.com/archives/003110.html Introducing \u2018Daggerin Condoms\u2019 by Vybz Kartel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208054943/http://www.yardflex.com/archives/003110.html |date=8 February 2011 }}. YardFlex. 2 September 2008.</ref>\nStreet Vybz Rum production was stopped in 2011 because of a disagreement between him and Corey Todd. However, the collaboration resumed in 2012 as the two settled their differences, and despite Kartel's ongoing incarceration.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boomstation.net/2012/08/24/vybz-kartel-corey-todd-officially-re-launch-street-vybz-rum|title=Vybz Kartel, Corey Todd Officially Re-launch Street Vybz Rum|publisher=Boomstation|accessdate=25 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20141225033330/http://boomstation.net/2012/08/24/vybz-kartel-corey-todd-officially-re-launch-street-vybz-rum|archivedate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 2009\u2013present: ''King of the Dancehall'' ===\nIn 2009 his song featuring female Jamaican deejay [[Spice (singer)|Spice]], \"Romping Shop\", debuted on the ''Billboard'' Top 100 Singles chart,<ref>[http://www.dancehall.mobi/2009/07/13/ramping-shop-hits-the-billboard-chart/ Ramping Shop Hits The Billboard Chart] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100906222823/http://www.dancehall.mobi/2009/07/13/ramping-shop-hits-the-billboard-chart/ |date=6 September 2010 }}. Dancehall.Mobi. Retrieved 16 February 2011.</ref> and \"Dollar Sign\" was in regular rotation on urban radio stations in the US.<ref>[http://www.wrfg.org/features/shows/shows-desc.asp?showid=20 WRFG Radio Free Georgia] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927122317/http://www.wrfg.org/features/shows/shows-desc.asp?showid=20 |date=27 September 2011 }}. Retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref>\n\nHis 2010 single \"Clarks\" was one of his biggest international successes, remaining in the top three reggae singles and gaining the most radio plays in North America for 40 weeks.<ref>[http://www.jamaicans.com/news/announcements/ClarksDeMixtapeRawHitsStores.shtml Clarks: De Mixtape Raw Hits Stores] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110112201707/http://www.jamaicans.com/news/announcements/ClarksDeMixtapeRawHitsStores.shtml |date=12 January 2011 }}. Jamaicans.com. 5 January 2011.</ref> \"Clarks\" was also featured on the TV series ''So You Think You Can Dance Canada'',<ref>[http://www.harringtonkommunication.com/?p=978 So You Think You Can Dance - Canada (Vybz Kartel - 'Clarks')] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006072904/http://www.harringtonkommunication.com/?p=978 |date=6 October 2014 }}. Harrington Kommunication. 3 September 2010.</ref> and on a CNN segment on dancehall dance.<ref>[http://www.thesweet7.com/2011/01/cnn-reports-jamaican-dancehall-goes.html CNN Reports Jamaican Dancehall Goes Global]. The Sweet 7. 21 January 2011.</ref> When his singles \"Clarks\", \"Clarks 2 (Clarks Again)\" and \"Clarks 3 (Wear Weh Yuh Have)\" featured the British shoe brand [[C&J Clark|Clarks]] in 2010, its sales numbers and prices in Jamaica increased considerably.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://repeatingislands.com/2010/07/09/sales-of-clarks-shoes-skyrocket-in-jamaica-thanks-to-vybz-kartel|title=Sales of Clarks shoes skyrocket in Jamaica thanks to Vybz Kartel|publisher=Repeatingislands.com|accessdate=25 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226112913/http://repeatingislands.com/2010/07/09/sales-of-clarks-shoes-skyrocket-in-jamaica-thanks-to-vybz-kartel/|archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref> In 2011, he released his own shoe line, named Addi's, as well as his own line of \"cake soap\", a type of soap primarily used for clothes. Cake soap is less commonly utilised for skincare, to treat skin conditions such as acne. However, Kartel's brand was intended for the purpose of skin lightening or bleaching.<ref name=shoesoap>Henry, Krista. [http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20110107/ent/ent1.html Kartel to start own shoe brand] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315011105/http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20110107/ent/ent1.html |date=15 March 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Star''; retrieved 25 December 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20110207/ent/ent2.html|title=Kartel's Addi's brand hits the market|publisher=Jamaica Star|accessdate=25 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110816001253/http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20110207/ent/ent2.html|archivedate=16 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/10/17/vybz-kartel-releases-skin-bleaching-line-while-awaiting-trial-for-murder|title=Vybz Kartel Releases Skin Bleaching Line While Awaiting Trial For Murder|publisher=Rapfix.mtv.com|accessdate=25 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226102815/http://rapfix.mtv.com/2011/10/17/vybz-kartel-releases-skin-bleaching-line-while-awaiting-trial-for-murder/|archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nMTV's ''Vice Guide to Dancehall'' featured Kartel at his weekly dance party, Street Vybz Thursday.<ref>Henry, Krista. [http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20101119/ent/ent3.html Dancehall episode for MTV series] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224174309/http://www.jamaica-star.com/thestar/20101119/ent/ent3.html |date=24 December 2010 }}. ''Jamaica Star''; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref> Vybz Kartel has also hosted his own reality television show \"Teacha's Pet\" on CVM Jamaica broadcast channel, the first reality television show hosted by a dancehall artist in Jamaica. The premise of \"Teacha's Pet\" found 20 women living in a Kingston house vying for the artist's affection; the show's lascivious content elicited condemnation of its sponsor, telecommunications company LIME. The show came to a halt with the artist's arrest on [[murder]] charges in September 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnweeklynews.com/entertainment/77-entertainment/2982-vybz-kartel-on-murder-rap|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130410171851/http://www.cnweeklynews.com/entertainment/77-entertainment/2982-vybz-kartel-on-murder-rap|url-status=dead|archive-date=10 April 2013|title=Vybz Kartel on murder rap|publisher=Cnweeklynews.com|accessdate=25 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, while in prison, Kartel released his most internationally successful album, ''King of the Dancehall'', which peaked at number 2 on the US [[Billboard charts|''Billboard'' Reggae Charts]]. The album included the single \"Fever\" which topped various local music charts and became his most successful on streaming websites.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKartel re-teamed with ''Kingston Story'' producer [[Dre Skull]] for the single \"Real Bad Gal\" in 2017. Two of his seven children, have continued his musical legacy, as Jaheim, also known as Little Vybz, and Akheel Raheim Palmer, also known as Little Addi, have been releasing music since 2014 as a duo known as PG 13 (also known as Kartel Sons).<ref>http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Vybz-Kartel-s-sons-to-continue-music-legacy-</ref> In 2019, both were featured on the \"Fully Gaza\" riddim, on separate songs, with Likkle Vybz teaming with father Vybz on the title track \"Fully Gaza\", while Likkle Addi performs solo on \"Dolla Sign\" which interpolates portions of the chorus from his father's single of the same name, on the Goodlife riddim, from 2009.<ref>https://www.discogs.com/artist/3885536-PG13-Little-Vybz-Little-Addi</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o6ZXGdE-1rI</ref>\n\nIn January 2020, Kartel released a 10 track album, \"To Tanesha\", which was dedicated to his common-law wife and mother of his three children, Tanesha Johnson.  They co-produced the album with their respective record labels: Short Boss Muzik and Vybz Kartel Muzik. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dancehallmag.com/2020/01/10/music/vybz-kartels-new-album-to-tanesha-is-out-now.html|title=Vybz Kartel\u2019s New Album \u2018To Tanesha\u2019 Is Out Now|last=McLeod|first=Sheri-kae|publisher=DancehallMag|date=January 10, 2020|accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Arrest and imprisonment==\n===Charges===\nOn 29 September 2011, Kartel was arrested by police for marijuana possession. Jamaica's Major Investigation Taskforce (MIT) later charged him with the [[murder]] of a Jamaican businessman, Barrington Burton, [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] and illegal possession of a [[firearm]].<ref name=\"Meschino\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/466879/vybz-kartel-jamaican-dancehall-star-charged-with-murder|title=Vybz Kartel, Jamaican Dancehall Star, Charged with Murder|last=Meschino|first=Patricia|work=Billboard|accessdate=23 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331022658/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/466879/vybz-kartel-jamaican-dancehall-star-charged-with-murder|archivedate=31 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nWhile in prison in 2012, his book ''The Voice Of The Jamaican Ghetto: Incarcerated but not Silenced'', co-written with business associate Michael Dawson, was published.<ref>Campbell, Curtis (2013) \"[http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20130811/ent/ent1.html Vybz Kartel's Book Offered At University - 'Voice Of The Ghetto' Gets Princeton Endorsement] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130812071136/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20130811/ent/ent1.html |date=12 August 2013 }}\", ''[[Jamaica Gleaner]]'', 11 August 2013; retrieved 11 August 2013</ref>\n\nThough Kartel was granted bail for the Burton murder on March 23rd, 2012 for JMD$3,000,000, he remained in jail in connection with a second murder, of one Clive 'Lizard' Williams, of Waterford, St Catherine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=36105|title=Vybz Kartel granted bail, but remains jailed|date=23 March 2012|work=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=24 March 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120323215048/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=36105|archivedate=23 March 2012}}</ref> He was charged, along with two others including Vanessa \"Gaza Slim\" Saddler, with perverting the course of justice, after Saddler allegedly claimed that Williams had robbed her in order to mislead the police into believing that he was still alive.<ref name=\"Mundle\">Mundle, Tanesha (2012) \"[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Nov-12-trial-date-for-Kartel Nov 12 trial date for Kartel] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120901040619/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Nov-12-trial-date-for-Kartel |date=1 September 2012 }}\", ''[[Jamaica Observer]]'', 30 August 2012; retrieved 1 September 2012.</ref> Kartel's trial was originally scheduled for January 21st, 2013, but had to be postponed due to a lack of jurors, and was rescheduled for July 11th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Vybz-Kartel-trial-faces-further-delay|title=Vybz Kartel trial faces further delay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226084424/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Vybz-Kartel-trial-faces-further-delay|archivedate=26 December 2014|access-date=12 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Trial===\n\nOn July 24th, a jury found Kartel not guilty of the charge of murder of Barrington Burton. However, Kartel remained in custody pending the second murder case.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vybz Kartel not guilty... Acquitted after prosecution offers no further evidence|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=46701|work=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=26 July 2013|date=24 July 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725173015/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=46701|archivedate=25 July 2013}}</ref> His trial for the murder of Clive Williams started on November 18th, 2013 and on March 13th, 2014, he was found guilty by an eleventh jury-member (10-1) of the murder of 27-year-old Clive \u2018Lizard\u2019 Williams.<ref>{{cite web|author=Gayle, Barbara|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=51661|title=Guilty - Vybz Kartel, three co-accused convicted, Shane Williams freed|work=Jamaica Gleaner|date=13 March 2014|accessdate=13 March 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140314013757/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=51661|archivedate=14 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McFadden|first=David|title=Jamaican rapper, 3 others convicted of murder|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/security-boosted-jamaica-rappers-trial-ending|work=Associated Press|accessdate=13 March 2014|date=13 March 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20140313045331/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/security-boosted-jamaica-rappers-trial-ending|archivedate=13 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Guilty\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-26573328|title=Jamaica dancehall star Vybz Kartel guilty of murder|date=14 March 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140319080642/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-26573328|archivedate=19 March 2014}}</ref> The 65-day trial was said to have been the longest in Jamaica's history.<ref name=\"Rollingstone_20140405\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/after-life-sentence-an-uncertain-fate-for-vybz-kartel-20140405 |title=After Life Sentence for Murder Conviction, an Uncertain Fate for Vybz Kartel |newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=5 April 2014 |author=Jesse Serwer |accessdate=31 December 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106232545/http://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/after-life-sentence-an-uncertain-fate-for-vybz-kartel-20140405 |archivedate=6 January 2015  }}</ref>\n\n===Conviction===\n\nOn April 3rd, 2014, Kartel was sentenced to life imprisonment. Justice Lennox Campbell said he would be eligible for parole after serving 35 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=52072|title=Vybz Kartel sentenced to life in prison, to serve 35 years before parole|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=26 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226051519/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/latest/article.php?id=52072|archivedate=26 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/jamaica-vybz-kartel-gets-life-murder-181325802.html|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=4 April 2014|title=In Jamaica, Vybz Kartel gets life for murder|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407105028/http://news.yahoo.com/jamaica-vybz-kartel-gets-life-murder-181325802.html|archivedate=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\n\nKartel's 2004 UK MOBO award nomination was withdrawn amidst controversy over homophobic content of his lyrics.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3636696.stm Mobo drops 'homophobic' artists] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122165053/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/3636696.stm |date=22 November 2008 }} BBC News, 8 September 2004</ref>\n\n===Skin whitening===\nKartel has come under controversy over perceived [[skin whitening]], or \"bleaching\", leading him to claim the use of \"cake soap\" to lighten his skin.<ref name=rub>Hunter, Nadisha. [http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20101229/lead/lead1.html Rub it out] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110315070512/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20101229/lead/lead1.html |date=15 March 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Gleaner''. 29 December 2010; retrieved 25 December 2014.</ref><ref name=trib>Farah. [http://www.tribune242.com/hurricane/02022011_inyaear-vybz-kartel_features_pg11 Vybz Kartel under fire for skin bleaching] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110322051017/http://www.tribune242.com/hurricane/02022011_inyaear-vybz-kartel_features_pg11 |date=22 March 2011 }}. ''The Tribune (Bahamas)''. 2 February 2011; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref> The Blue Power Group, Jamaican manufacturer of the popular cake soap (or \"blue soap\"), has refuted claims it changes skin color.<ref>Roache, Alicia. [http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/business/Cake-soap-company-lightens-Kartel-s-claim_8283170 Cake soap company lightens Kartel's claim] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110115054411/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/business/Cake-soap-company-lightens-Kartel-s-claim_8283170 |date=15 January 2011 }}. ''Jamaica Observer''. 12 January 2011; retrieved 26 December 2014.</ref> Kartel stated the soap used to lighten his skin was his own company brand, which he intended to release on the local market and to overseas clients.<ref name=shoesoap/>\n\n===Airwave ban===\nIn September 2011, the National Communications Network of [[Guyana]] banned Vybz Kartel from the airwaves\u2014the first such action against a specific artist.<ref>{{cite news| author =[[Associated Press]]| title =Guyana bans Kartel's obscene music| newspaper =[[Associated Press]] via [[The Jamaica Observer]]| date =21 September 2011| url =http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Guyana-bans-Kartel-s-obscene-music| accessdate =28 April 2015| url-status =live| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150620115811/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/news/Guyana-bans-Kartel-s-obscene-music| archivedate =20 June 2015| df =dmy-all}}</ref> NCN spokesman Martin Goolsarran said his music contained \"obscene lyrics\" and brought \"nothing positive\" to the entertainment industry, on Wednesday, 21st of September after a week of internal debate. He said NCN was reviewing the lyrics of other musicians and could ban them as well.\n\n===Feud with Mavado===\nA public feud between Kartel and former collaborator [[Mavado (singer)|Mavado]] arose towards the end of 2006, stemming from Vybz' much publicised departure from the dancehall conglomerate group The Alliance. The feud resulted in numerous diss tracks released, in which each artist dissed the other and their associates over popular dancehall rhythms.<ref name=Voice>Dreisinger, Baz. [http://www.villagevoice.com/content/printVersion/1686421/ Reggae's Civil War Why Mavado and Vybz Kartel might be the Biggie and Tupac of Dancehall] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629133420/http://www.villagevoice.com/content/printVersion/1686421/ |date=29 June 2011 }}. ''Village Voice'', 2 March 2010; accessed 26 December 2014.</ref> In a police-overseen press conference in March 2007, both Mavado and Vybz Kartel publicly announced an end to hostilities and apologized to fans.<ref>Kaylia Williams: [http://www.yardflex.com/archives/001154.html Unprecedented Press Conference ends feud between Vybz Kartel and Mavado] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114172634/http://www.yardflex.com/archives/001154.html |date=14 January 2009 }}. YardFlex.com Archives, 2 March 2007; accessed 27 January 2011</ref>\n\nHowever, by the summer of 2008, tensions flared with a renewal of \"diss tracks\" from each artist, and a lyrical clash between the two at Sting 2008 left mixed views as to the \"winner\".<ref>[http://www.yardflex.com/archives/003051.html Mavado and Vybz Kartel at it again] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721130105/http://www.yardflex.com/archives/003051.html |date=21 July 2011 }}. YardFlex.com. 22 August 2008. Retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref><ref>Black, Francine. [http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20081229/ent/ent1.html Entertainment insiders say... STING CLASH WAS A DRAW] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324150000/http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20081229/ent/ent1.html |date=24 March 2012 }}, ''Jamaica Star''. 29 December 2008; retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref>\n\nMost of 2009 saw a continuation of the public feud, which dominated Jamaican media and, to a certain extent, Jamaican culture, with the two artists' factions, ''Gaza'' (Kartel) and ''Gully'' (Mavado), being adopted by Jamaican youth, in some cases leading to street violence.<ref>Boyne, Ian. [http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20090920/focus/focus1.html The Gully-Gaza war] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121007225434/http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20090920/focus/focus1.html |date=7 October 2012 }}. ''Jamaica Gleaner''. 20 September 2009. Retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref><ref>[http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20090804/news/news1.html BEATEN FOR 'GULLY' MUSIC - Driver assaulted, householder threatened after playing Mavado songs] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120324150029/http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20090804/news/news1.html |date=24 March 2012 }}, ''Jamaica Star'', 4 August 2009; retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref>\n\nOn December 8th, 2009, Kartel and Mavado met with Jamaican Prime Minister [[Bruce Golding]] in an attempt to end the feud, which had by that time fueled mob attacks in some of the [[inner city]] neighborhoods of [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]].<ref>[http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20091208/lead/lead6.html Prime Minister to meet with Kartel, Mavado] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213004509/http://www.jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20091208/lead/lead6.html |date=13 December 2009 }}. ''Jamaica Gleaner''. 8 December 2009. Retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref> The two had performed together on-stage the previous night in a sign of goodwill at the West Kingston Jamboree, a concert promoted by [[drug lord]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-14742342|work=BBC News|title=Jamaica drug lord 'Dudus' Coke admits racketeering|date=31 August 2011|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020203234/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-14742342|archivedate=20 October 2011}}</ref> [[Christopher \"Dudus\" Coke]].<ref name=Voice/> After the truce in December 2009, the two artists were scheduled to perform a unity concert in March 2010 in [[Barbados]], which was later cancelled by Bajan Prime Minister [[David Thompson (Barbadian politician)|David Thompson]].<ref>[http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Mavado-Kartel-show-off-in-Barbados_7506329 Barbados PM says no to Mavado, Vybz Kartel show] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612160444/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/entertainment/Mavado-Kartel-show-off-in-Barbados_7506329 |date=12 June 2010 }}. ''Jamaica Observer''. 26 March 2010; retrieved 15 April 2011.</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 2003\n** [[Stone Love Movement|Stone Love]]'s 30th Anniversary\n*** DJ of the Year 2005\n* 2008\n** CUMA (Caribbean Urban Music Awards)\n* 2009\n** EME Awards<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.emeawards.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46:2009-winners-a-nominees&catid=27:new-to-joomla&Itemid=2 | title=2009 EME Awards | publisher=EME Awards | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100117102515/http://www.emeawards.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46:2009-winners-a-nominees&catid=27:new-to-joomla&Itemid=2 | archivedate=17 January 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n*** Male DJ of the Year\n*** Lyricist/Songwriter of the Year\n*** Song of the Year (Romping Shop ft. [[Spice (singer)|Spice]])\n* 2010\n** EME Awards<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.emeawards.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=18&Itemid=27 | title=2010 EME Awards | publisher=EME Awards | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218094143/http://www.emeawards.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=18&Itemid=27 | archivedate=18 February 2010 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Nominations===\n* [[The Source (magazine)|Source]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ttgapers.com/index.php?module=News&func=display&sid=946 |title=Vybz Kartel pleased to be nominated for a Source award |publisher=ttgapers.com |date= |accessdate=8 March 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Vibe (magazine)|VIBE]]\n* UK [[Music of Black Origin Awards|MOBO]] awards\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\" | Album details\n! scope=\"col\" | Peak chart positions<ref>{{cite web |author=Artist Biography by David Jeffries |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vybz-kartel-mn0000261309/awards |title=Vybz Kartel &#124; Awards |publisher=AllMusic |date=7 January 1979 |accessdate=3 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140515141326/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/vybz-kartel-mn0000261309/awards |archivedate=15 May 2014  }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.8em;font-size:90%;\" |[[Top Reggae Albums|US Reggae]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Up 2 Di Time''\n|\n* Released: 28 October 2003\n* Label: Greensleeves\n* Format: CD, digital\n|align=center|\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Timeless''\n|\n* Released: 23 February 2004\n* Label: Freedom Sounds\n* Format: CD, digital\n|\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''More Up 2 Di Time''\n|\n* Released: 14 September 2004\n* Label: Greensleeves\n* Format: CD, digital\n|align=center|\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''J.M.T.''\n|\n* Released: 15 November 2005\n* Label: Greensleeves\n* Format: CD, digital\n|align=center|\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''[[The Teacher's Back]]''\n|\n* Released: 18 November 2008\n* Label: JVC/Victor\n* Format: CD, digital\n|align=center|\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Most Wanted''\n|\n* Released: 26 May 2009\n* Label: Greensleeves\n* Format: CD, digital\n|align=center|\u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|''Pon Di Gaza 2.0'' <ref>[http://jamaica-star.com/thestar/20100213/ent/ent1.html Kartel releases Pon Di Gaza 2.0] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324032458/http://www.jamaica-star.com/thestar/20100213/ent/ent1.html |date=24 March 2010 }}. ''Jamaica Star''. Retrieved 16 February 2011.</ref>\n|\n* Released: 26 February 201